title: Top Things to do in Langkawi | Traveloka Travel Guide
tags: things to do in langkawi|langkawi|langkawi cable car|langkawi sky bridge|pulau langkawi|langkawi island|langkawi malaysia|langkawi beach|langkawi travel guide|langkawi attractions|what to do in langkawi|langkawi trip|langkawi 2018|cenang beach
description:
Discover the the top things to do in Langkawi with Aina and Rhys!
**TRAVELOKA TRAVEL GUIDE CONTEST ** - LANGKAWI MALAYSIA

Traveloka is giving away hotel vouchers worth RM50 each to 10 lucky winners who reside in Malaysia! Participating is super easy. Just comment, like and subscribe to our channel and you‚Äôll stand a chance to win one of the vouchers!

Langkawi Travel Guide Overview: (0:18-0:25)

1. Jet Ski Island Hopping (0:41-2:09)

Ride your own jet ski as you zip across the blue Langkawi island ocean waves, exploring Langkawi‚Äôs many tiny islands. The 3-hour package costs RM698 per jet ski.

Be sure to stop by Dayang Bunting (Pregnant Maiden) Island, which has a picturesque freshwater lake. According to local folklore, couples having difficulty in conceiving a child should take a dip in the lake‚Äôs blessed waters. 

Many of the remote Langkawi islands are uninhabited, so you‚Äôll probably come across a secret Langkawi beach or two that you‚Äôll have all to yourself. 

2. Parasailing (2:10-3:33)

Cenang Beach is probably Langkawi‚Äôs most popular beach, where you can find all sorts of water sports and activities available. A favorite among visitors is parasailing, where you can soar through the sky and take in the view of Pulau Langkawi from up above. It costs around RM300 per person.

3. Paradise 101 (3:34-5:19)

One of the more popular Langkawi attractions is Paradise 101, a private man-made island located off Telaga Harbour Marina that‚Äôs home to a fun, floating obstacle course. 

For super-fast thrills, jump on the Jet Pilot or the banana boat, which will take you careening across the water. Or even the Zip Line, where you‚Äôll scream as you fly through the air. 

Paradise Day Pass
Adult: RM240 
Child: RM120

4. SkyCab & SkyBridge (5:20-7:09)

Visit two of Langkawi‚Äôs most iconic attractions, the SkyCab (similar to a Langkawi cable car) and  Langkawi Sky Bridge, for breathtaking 360-degree views you won‚Äôt forget. Get on the SkyCab at the base of Machinchang Mountain, which will slowly take you up the mountain so you can appreciate the sights. 

The Langkawi Sky Bridge is said to be the longest free span and curved suspension bridge in the world, with its highest point at 708 meters above sea level.

SkyCab
MyKad Holders: RM40 (Adult); RM30 (Child)
Non-MyKad Holders: RM55 (Adult); RM40 (Child)

SkyBridge
Adult: RM5
Child: RM3

5. Langkawi Wildlife Park (7:10-8:32)

Wondering what to do in Langkawi? Check out the Langkawi Wildlife Park, where you can get up-close with over 150 species of animals from around the world. If you‚Äôre brave enough to face hungry creatures, buy food packs so you can feed them by hand. 

Entrance Fees
MyKad Holders: RM24 (Adult); RM16 (Child/Senior)
Non-MyKad Holders: RM39 (Adult); RM22 (Child/Senior)

6. Langkawi Adventure & Xtreme Park (8:33-10:09)

To make your Langkawi trip worth it, visit this outdoor adventure park built for true thrillseekers. Here, you can try to keep your precarious balance on a skybike ‚Äì a bicycle on a wire suspended 50 meters off the ground or roar through the jungle on an ATV on the 90-minute ATV adventure track

7. Kilim Karst Geoforest Park (10:10-11:17)

On the northern part of the Langkawi island is the Kilim Karst Geoforest Park, a nature reserve featuring mangroves, caves and limestone formations. Cruise down the river to view the mangrove trees that line the river. Then, visit the bat cave for a close-up view of the nocturnal residents. 

Then, head to the eagle feeding spot to watch the majestic birds of prey as they swoop down to the water to scoop up their food. 

Fee
RM200-500 per boat, depending on the length of the tour

8. Bella Vista Waterfront Hotel & Resort Langkawi

Conveniently located along waterfront in the town of Kuah, Langkawi, the hotel offers guests easy access to all the top activities and attractions in Pulau Langkawi. 

Bella Vista has rooms suitable for every budget, from the chic-yet-affordable Deluxe Room at RM234 per night to the Loft Room for RM336 per night, a suite that comes with a charming daybed by the window ‚Äì the perfect spot for a bit of reading! If you‚Äôre looking to ‚Äògo big or go home‚Äô, book a stay at the impressive Garden Suite ‚Äì for RM648 a night where you‚Äôll have access to either a private patio in the hotel‚Äôs gardens, or a private balcony and breathtaking views of the Andaman sea.

Thank you for watching. If you enjoyed this Langkawi 2018 Travel Guide, please subscribe to our channel and give us a like! Have some awesome locations in mind that you‚Äôd like us to cover? Let us know in the comments section down below.

description:
Art Thomya, a Thai singer/songwriter, will show you GREAT LOCAL FOOD in Phuket, the largest island in Thailand and one of the world's most famous islands. Apart from amazingly beautiful beaches, Phuket has a large variety of cultures which reflect in its food. From street food to restaurants, Art will show you how amazing these local dishes are. Let's go eat together!

++++++
Book Flight to Phuket from Bangkok : https://www.bangkokair.com
Follow Bangkok Airways :
YT : https://www.youtube.com/user/FlyBangk...
FB : https://www.facebook.com/FlyBangkokAir

++++++
Local dishes and restaurants featured in this video

Yao Yentafo
- Yentafo (Pink Noodle Soup)
- Egg Noodles with Fish Balls
- Giant Fish Balls with Seafood Sauce
- O Taw (Fried Small Oysters with Flour and Eggs)
- Pork Satay
- Fresh Spring Rolls

Jee Jai Bung Neaw
- Lobah
- Oh Aew (Jelly & Beans with Shaved Ice)
- Pork Ribs and Fried Vermicelli

Tung Ka Cafe
- Fried Mieng Vegetables with Eggs
- Stir-fried Stink Beans with Shrimp Paste
- Spicy Pineapple Soup with Prawns (Southern Thai Style)

title: Trang An & Tam Coc: Karst Scenery of Ninh Binh, Vietnam in 4K Ultra HD
tags: Trang An|Tam Coc|Ninh Binh|Van Long Nature reserve|Van Long|Hang Mua|karst|limestone|peak|Vietnam|documentary|scenic|tour|travel|tourism|adventure|AX100|4K|4K video ultra hd|Ultra HD|4K Ultra HD|UHD|HD|milosh9k|Amazing Places on Our Planet|travel 4K|4k documentary|vietnam 4k|tam coc 4k|trang an 4k
description:
The area around the city of Ninh Binh in Vietnam is famous for its Karst scenery: rivers flowing between karst peaks, through caves and rice fields. Trang An Landscape Complex is an UNESCO World Heritage Site, boat ride takes the visitors through 9 caves/tunnels. The Hang Mua peak offers views over the nearby karst peaks, rice fields and rivers. In Tam Coc another boat ride takes the visitors through 3 caves/tunnels and between rice fields. Van Long Nature Reserve has more peaks and caves and beautiful reflections in its calm waters.  

Recorded April 2018 in 4K Ultra HD with Sony AX100.

Music:
 Rildrim - The Lonely Wizard - 6 - The Lonely Wizard
 Rildrim - Moving Inward - 5 - Talking to the Trees

Best Street Food in Penang | Traveloka Travel Guide
tags: malaysia street food|street food in penang|penang street food|penang georgetown|street food in malaysia|georgetown penang|penang food|malaysian food|food in penang|asian food|asian street food|street food malaysia|penang|penang food guide|street food|halal food in penang
description:
Explore the best Malaysia Penang street food with Aina and Abam Bocey!
**TRAVELOKA TRAVEL GUIDE CONTEST ** - PENANG

Traveloka is giving away hotel vouchers worth RM50 each to 10 lucky winners who reside in Malaysia! Participating is super easy. Just comment, like and subscribe to our channel and you‚Äôll stand a chance to win one of the vouchers!

Best Malaysia Street Food in Penang Guide including Georgetown Penang: (0:22-0:27)

1. Bee Hwa Cafe (0:28-1:31)

If you're looking for some delicious halal food in Penang Georgetown, Bee Hwa Cafe's well-loved Char Kuey Teow (CKT) is a must try.  

Order a plate of the special CKT, and you‚Äôll get savory crabsticks and fishballs added to it. 

2. A1 Buah Berangan (1:32-2:05)

Down the road from Bee Hwa Cafe on Jalan Penang is A1 Buah Berangan (or roasted chestnuts). You'll understand why the stall has been open in Penang for 15 years the moment you crack open a chestnut and pop one into your mouth.

3. Hameed Pata Mee Sotong (2:06-3:21)

Located at Fort Cornwallis Food Court in Esplanade Park, Hameed Pata Mee Sotong serves up platefuls of steaming hot mee sotong, a popular Penang street food in Malaysia that consist of a spicy noodle dish doused in cuttlefish sambal. A small plate of it costs RM5 while a bigger serving costs RM7. 

Also available at the Georgetown Penang food court is a refreshing glass of coconut shake. Blended with homemade coconut ice cream, the creamy and sweet beverage blends perfectly with your mee sotong. 

4. Apom Balik (3:22-4:10)

Located at the front of the post office on Lebuh Downing, Apom Balik is a popular Malaysian street food stall that sells delicious apam balik.

The cart is open from 12pm - 6pm every day, where you can order additional fillings such as peanut butter or chocolate. 

5. Street Grill Burger Bakar (4:11-5:06)

An asian street food you don't want to miss, this street stall on Jalan Sungai Pinang, which offers homemade chargrilled burgers overflowing with melted mozzarella cheese and a special sauce. 

The stall is open from 6.30pm - 12am, but we recommend that you head there early before the crowd gathers. 

6. Deen Maju (5:07-7:18)

A Penang Georgetown street food staple, you can‚Äôt say you‚Äôve eaten the best of Penang‚Äôs food without having tried nasi kandar, so head to Jalan Gurdwara for one of the island‚Äôs best nasi kandar shops. 

Choose from a wide array of dishes to eat with your rice, from the flavorful fish roe curry to the crunchy 15-spice fried chicken, which are both specialties at Deen Maju. 

7. Argyll Road Roti Canai (7:19-8:31)

Dating back to 1955, Argyll Road Roti Canai is one of George Town‚Äôs oldest eateries. From its beginnings as a tiny Penang street stall, it has since expanded to a proper shophouse. 

The Malaysian breakfast staple is served drenched in a delicious curry of your choice, such as chicken, beef or mutton. 

8. Nasi Melayu Lidiana (8:32-10:24)

Tucked in the Tanjung Bungah Food Court, this homely asian food eatery has been in operation for over 40 years. You‚Äôll be spoiled for choice as you can pick from a wide range of dishes to pile on your plate of rice. 

Must-try dishes are chicken cooked in soy sauce (ayam kicap) and the sambal-stuffed grilled pomfret.

9. Kambing Bakaq Tuk Hang (10:25-11:39)

Located on the corner of Hilir Paya Terubong in Relau, Kambing Bakaq Tuk Hang specializes in delicious and savory grilled lamb. Dunk a chunk of their honey-glazed lamb in the special homemade BBQ sauce for the best experience. A must-try food in Penang.

Each portion of lamb costs RM12 (small), RM15 (medium) and RM20 (large).

If you're a fan of chicken, you can also order chicken from e‚ÄôCorner, the restaurant next door that has some of the best grilled chicken around. 

10. Penang Road Famous Teochew Chendul (11:40-12:45)

A well-loved food in Penang, there‚Äôs nothing better than downing a bowl of icy, sweet cendol after a walk around George Town. If that‚Äôs what you‚Äôre after, then make a beeline for Penang Road Famous Teochew Chendul, located on Keng Kwee Street.  

11. Project Nasi Lemak Box (12:46-14:15)

A popular Malaysia street food in Penang, check out Project Nasi Lemak Box.

Located at Padang Kota Lama, it‚Äôs relatively new compared to many of the veterans on this list. They use natural dye from butterfly pea flowers to give their nasi lemak a pretty purple-blue color, similar to nasi kerabu. Choose your own sides such as fried chicken, fried fish and assam prawns.

For a true high-end indulgence Malaysia street food, order the nasi lemak lobster (RM79), served with a succulent lobster smothered in cheese and blow-torched to crispy perfection. 


Thank you for watching. If you enjoyed the video, please subscribe to our channel and give us a like! Have some awesome locations in mind that you‚Äôd like us to cover? Let us know in the comments section down below.

To know even more about Penang, visit: https://www.traveloka.com/en-my/travel/malaysia/penang

title: Worst day, best food in Thailand - Songkran Festival
tags: recipe30 thailand|recipe30 thai|recipe30 vlogs|popular food destination|travel phuket thailand|travel thailand|thailand best accommodation|thai new year|thai water festival|songkran festival thailand|thai travel videos|thailand travel|phuket food blog|travel thailand vlog|street food thailand 2018|thailand travel vlog|thailand travel video|travel blogs|water festival|songkran|songkran festival|songkran 2019|songkran phuket
description:
This is the worst day to travel to Thailand!  But it can also be a lot of refreshing fun in this hot weather.   Thailand. We hadn't realised that it was the Thai new year known as Songkran, a water festival, and we just happen to be there that day.  Talk about luck, or not! We got attacked with water guns, hosed, splashed and soaked right through.  Don't carry expensive electronics in the streets as there's no limits.  Laptops, cameras, phones will get soaked!!! Phuket is definitely a popular food destination.  See tasty street food, Thai restaurants and a lobster thermidor recipe in this food and travel vlog. Plus the unusual Beyond Patong Hotel with it's underwater theme. Enjoy the worst day in Thailand by Recipe30.  Joel.

title: Top Things to do in Penang | Traveloka Travel Guide
tags: penang|penang malaysia|things to do in penang|things to do in George Town|George Town Penang|George Town Malaysia|penang attractions|what to do in penang|penang travel guide|places to visit in penang|interesting places in penang|where to go in penang|things to do in penang georgetown|Georgetown Penang|abam bocey
description:
Come discover the top things to do in Penang Malaysia with Aina and her new travel buddy Abam Bocey!
**TRAVELOKA TRAVEL GUIDE CONTEST ** - PENANG TRAVEL GUIDE

Traveloka is giving away hotel vouchers worth RM50 each to 10 lucky winners who reside in Malaysia! Participating is super easy. Just comment, like and subscribe to our channel and you‚Äôll stand a chance to win one of the vouchers!

To know more about Traveloka visit - https://www.traveloka.com/en-my/ & don't forget to check out our latest Raya Promo for great Flight & Hotel deals at https://www.traveloka.com/en-my/

#ThingsToDo #Penang #TravelokaTravelGuide 

List of locations including Georgetown Penang attractions that will be explored in this episode: 0:18-0:23


1) Escape Park (0:24-2:37)

About 30 minutes away from Georgetown Penang, Escape is known for its family-friendly adventure theme park where you can zoom downhill on a tube and scramble through challenging rope courses or enjoy the awesome water park.

Walk-in Admission Fees:- 
Future Kid (0-3): Free 
Junior Kid (4-12): RM90
Big Kid (13-60): RM136
Super Kid (61+): RM90


2) Ghost Museum (2:38-4:03)
Learn about the origins and folklore of various ghosts from all around the world at the Penang Malaysia Ghost Museum. You can also try on cool costumes and pose with the exhibits, so bring along some friends!

Entrance Fees:- 
MyKad Holders: RM18 (Adult) ; RM10 (Child/Student/Senior)
Non-MyKad Holders: RM28 (Adult); RM16 (Child/Student/Senior)


3) Penang Street Art (4:04-5:41)
In Georgetown, Penang‚Äôs famed street art put the city on the map, turning mural hunting into a popular activity among visitors as they try to track down and take photos of famous pieces of art such as the ‚ÄòBoy on a Motorcycle‚Äô and ‚ÄòChildren on the Swings.‚Äô

Hop on a covered beca (trishaw), which can take you around the core heritage zone of George Town to view the murals for around RM40.


4) 3D Trick Art Museum (5:42-6:53)
Check out Penang's 3D Trick Art Museum that play on perspective and interactive props that put you in fantastical scenarios, adding a bit of fun to your usual holiday photos. There are also replicas of scenes from famous movies and well-known works of art, where you can snap photos at.

Entrance Fees:- 
MyKad Holders: RM15 (Adult); RM10 (Child/Senior)
Non-MyKad Holders: RM25 (Adult); RM15 (Child)


5) Tropical Spice Garden (6:54-8:10)
This 8-acre tropical garden is one of the popular Penang attractions and home to over 500 species of exotic flora and fauna. Located in Teluk Bahang, it‚Äôs on the northwest side of Penang island and is bordered by rainforest and sea. 

Choose between an audio tour or a guided tour to learn more about the many species of flowers, herbs and spices you‚Äôll come across in the garden.

Garden Audio Tours:- 
Adult: RM29 
Child: RM17
Senior/Student: RM23 

Live Guided Tours:- 
Adult: RM49 
Child: RM25
Senior/Student: RM39 


6) Penang Hill & The Habitat (8:11-9:56)
One of the best places to visit in Georgetown Penang is Penang Hill, also known as Bukit Bendera. It‚Äôs a favorite among nature lovers thanks to the diversity of flora and fauna you can find as you hike up the hill.

At the top of the hill, there‚Äôs many things to see and do such as The Habitat, which is Penang‚Äôs premier eco-tourism attraction, the Treetop Walk which gives you an unforgettable bird‚Äôs eye view of the jungle from up above and David Brown‚Äôs Restaurant & Tea Terrace, which serves appetizing Western dishes and afternoon tea. 


7) Phantamania Magic World (9:57-11:25)
For lovers of magic and sleight of hand, drop by Phantamania Magic World, a mini theme park where you can pretend you‚Äôre a magician for a day and perform your own tricks. 

Entrance Fees:- 
MyKad Holders: RM16 (Adult); RM12 (Child/Senior)
Non-MyKad Holders: RM27 (Adult); RM16 (Child/Senior)


8) The Top (11:27-12:32)
This attraction is located on the very tip top of Komtar Tower, Penang‚Äôs tallest building. Take the elevator 68 floors up, where you can get the best view of the city and its surroundings by walking on the Rainbow Skywalk, a transparent glass bridge that extends away from the building.

For those prone to feeling vertigo, visit the Coco Cabana, a bar and bistro with an extensive menu, located on the same level.

Entrance Fees:-
Adult: RM98
Child/Senior: RM58


9) Tropics Eight Suites (12:33-13:17)
Check out Tropics Eight Suites. Set on Jalan Gottlieb, it‚Äôs just down the road from Gurney Drive. With rates starting from RM240 a night, the suites are spacious and fitted with urban comforts such as a cozy living room and a well-equipped kitchen. Facilities include an all-day gym and a self-service laundry room.


Thank you for watching. If you enjoyed the video, please subscribe to our channel and give us a like! Have some awesome locations in mind that you‚Äôd like us to cover? Let us know in the comments section down below.

To know even more about Penang, visit: https://www.traveloka.com/en-my/travel/malaysia/penang

description:
Part two of my Thailand travel vlogs.  We arrived at this amazing luxury villa Amanzi.  As I'm used to staying in hotels, it was hard to believe the size of this place for two people.   Complete with staff and a personal Chef that cooked incredible Thai food recipes for lunch and dinner.   We had an incredible beach view only a short walk to the golden tropical sands of Kata Noi beach.  We drove to the local Thai market to buy our produce for lunch, and to see how coconut milk was made.  Watch easy to follow Thai recipes that you can make at home. description:
Art Thomya, a Thai singer/songwriter, will show you the 7 Must-Eats in PHANG NGA, a paradise for beach and island lovers. Phang Nga is located just one hour from Phuket and has two amazing marine national parks - Similan Islands and Surin Islands. Art was accompanied by his local friends, who are eager to show you the charms of their hometown. Let's take this journey together!

++++++
Book Flight to PHANG NGA via PHUKET airport : https://www.bangkokair.com
Follow Bangkok Airways :
YT : https://www.youtube.com/user/FlyBangkAir
FB : https://www.facebook.com/FlyBangkokAir

++++++
7 Must-Eats in PHANG NGA, Thailand
#1 Mieng Rao (Location : Takua Pa Sunday Market)
#2 Look Chok (Local Fruit)
#3 Sea Grapes (Green Seaweed, Phang Nga Cavier) (Location : Takua Pa Sunday Market)
#4 Fried Mieng Vegetable with Smoked Shrimps (‡∏ú‡∏±‡∏î‡πÄ‡∏´‡∏°‡∏µ‡∏¢‡∏á‡∏ú‡∏±‡∏î‡∏Å‡∏∏‡πâ‡∏á‡πÄ‡∏™‡∏µ‡∏¢‡∏ö) (Location : Takua Pa Sunday Market)
#5 Fried Sai Fish with Turmeric 
#6 Tao Sor Cake (Location Caption : Tao Sor Tuangrat )
#7 Local Menus From Various Cultures
- Handmade Egg Noodles (Location : Phang-Nga Noodles, Talad Kwang)
- Halal Food (Location : Halal Restaurant, Khao Lak)

++++++
Follow Art Thomya :
YT : https://www.youtube.com/ArtThomyaJourney https://www.youtube.com/ArtThomya
FB : https://www.facebook.com/ArtThomyaMusic

title: üáπüá≠ 7 MUST-DOS in PHANG NGA, THAILAND (near PHUKET)
description:
Art Thomya, a Thai singer/songwriter, will show you the 7 Must-Dos in PHANG NGA, a paradise for beach and island lovers. Phang Nga is located just one hour from Phuket and has two amazing marine national parks - Similan Islands and Surin Islands. Art was accompanied by his local friends, who are eager to show you the charms of their hometown. Let's take this journey together!

7 Must-Dos in PHANG NGA, Thailand

#3 Learn About Tsunami

Food is always the main purpose of my travels but visiting beautiful locations and luxury villas is high on my list.  This was our first day, we went to Patong beach for lunch. title: üáπüá≠ 7 MUST-SEES in PHANG NGA, THAILAND (near PHUKET)
tags: Art Thomya|‡∏≠‡∏≤‡∏£‡πå‡∏ó ‡∏ñ‡∏°‡∏¢‡∏≤|asean|southeast asia|‡∏≠‡∏≤‡πÄ‡∏ã‡∏µ‡∏¢‡∏ô|heyasean|‡πÄ‡∏Æ‡∏¢‡πå‡∏≠‡∏≤‡πÄ‡∏ã‡∏µ‡∏¢‡∏ô|‡πÄ‡∏ó‡∏µ‡πà‡∏¢‡∏ß‡∏≠‡∏≤‡πÄ‡∏ã‡∏µ‡∏¢‡∏ô|asia|‡πÄ‡∏≠‡πÄ‡∏ä‡∏µ‡∏¢|Bangkok Airways|‡∏ö‡∏≤‡∏á‡∏Å‡∏≠‡∏Å ‡πÅ‡∏≠‡∏£‡πå‡πÄ‡∏ß‡∏¢‡∏™‡πå|mekongmoments|‡∏û‡∏±‡∏á‡∏á‡∏≤|phang nga|thailand|amazing thailand|baan khaolak beach resort|khaolak|Surin Islands|similan islands|khao na yak|tai muang beach|samed nang she|khao ta poo|james bond island|khao ping kan|koh panyee|wat suwan khuha|phuket|krabi
description:
Art Thomya, a Thai singer/songwriter, will show you the 7 Must-Sees in PHANG NGA, a paradise for beach and island lovers. Phang Nga is located just one hour from Phuket and has two amazing marine national parks - Similan Islands and Surin Islands. Art was accompanied by his local friends, who are eager to show you the charms of their hometown. Let's take this journey together!

++++++
Book Flight to PHANG NGA via PHUKET airport : https://www.bangkokair.com
Follow Bangkok Airways :
YT : https://www.youtube.com/user/FlyBangkAir
FB : https://www.facebook.com/FlyBangkokAir

++++++
7 Must-Sees in PHANG NGA, Thailand
#1 Surin Islands National Park
#2 Similan Islands National Park
#3 Khao Na Yak (Tai Muang Beach)
#4 Samed Nang She Viewpoint
#5 Khao Ta Poo (James Bond Island) / Khao Ping Kan
#6 Koh Panyee
#7 Wat Suwan Khuha (Cave Temple)

++++++
Follow Art Thomya :
YT : https://www.youtube.com/ArtThomyaJourney https://www.youtube.com/ArtThomya
FB : https://www.facebook.com/ArtThomyaMusic
IG : https://instagram.com/ArtThomya

#PhangNga #Thailand #Beach

title: Langkawi to Kuala lumpur : Last day of my Malaysia trip
tags: TouristHelpline|MountainTrekker|Travel series|langkawi to kuala lumpur ferry|langkawi to kuala lumpur|langkawi to kuala lumpur train|langkawi to kuala lumpur by bus|langkawi to kuala lumpur dis
description:
This is the last video of my Malaysian travel series. Watch this video to see how I started my trip from Langkawi to Kuala Lumpur. I took a ferry from Langkawi jetty to Kuala Perlis. Ferry fare from Langkawi to Kuala Perlis is 18 Ringgit, and journey duration was around 1 hour. From Kuala Perlis to Kuala Lumpur I hitchhiked. Met a lot of wonderful people. In the whole trip of Malaysia, I met a lot of Malaysian fans of Bollywood star Shahrukh Khan. In this video, you will see another die-hard fan of SRK (Shahrukh Khan)

title: My stay in Langkawi, Malaysia (Hostel near Cenang beach)
tags: TouristHelpline|MountainTrekker|langkawi hostel|langkawi hotel|villa thai langkawi|street monkey backpacker hostel|Hitchhiking in Langkawi|rental bikes in langkawi|rental cars langkawi|car in
description:
Click here to book and read unbiased review: https://goo.gl/8r1A55
I started with hitchhiking in Langkawi. Met a few wonderful people of Langkawi. They dropped me at a hostel which I initially booked, but probably due to overbooking the hostel arranged a better stay in a nearby hostel. So I finally got to stay in 'Villa Thai' which is a hostel/hotel near Cenang beach. They have rooms as well as a dormitory for tourists. After that, I visited Cenang beach. In the video, you can see many hotels, guesthouses, hostel near Cenang beach. I Spent a good time walking on the beach and Cenang street.

description:
Khao Phing Kan or Ko Khao Phing Kan is a pair of islands on the west coast of Thailand, in the Phang Nga Bay, Andaman Sea. 
Enjoy a soothing 4k relax video from a secluded place from https://www.beautifulwashington.com and http://www.proartinc.net
Pacifying nature sounds, calming sounds of water and wonderful scenery.

The island is a part of the Ao Phang Nga National Park. Since 1974, when it was featured in the James Bond movie The Man with the Golden Gun, it is popularly called James Bond Island.

title: LIVING CHEAP IN THAILAND | UNDER $600 | CHIANGMAI VS BANGKOK | BUDGET LIFE 2018 |
tags: Divertliving|travel|blog|daily|vlog|digital nomad|thailand|workation|chiangmai cost of living|chiang mai|cost of living|cost of living in chiangmai|budget travel|cost of living thailand|travel show|apartments|digital nomad cost of living|thailand on budget|living in thailand|markets|cheap|low cost|asia|prices|moving to thailand|budget living|living on budget|bangkok vs chaingmai|LIVING IN THAILAND UNDER $600 CHIANGMAI VS BANGKOK | BUDGET LIFE 2018 ||lostleblanc
description:
AMERICAN AND THAI DISCUSS ABOUT COST OF LIVING IN THAILAND ( CHIANGMAI AND BANGKOK ) FIND THE USEFUL LINK AND INFOMATION BELOW : 

Hi friends !! As we travel full time, besides the big passion we have on traveling, money is one of the main factor keeping us going on the road, we are really careful when it comes to spending and saving money, that's why we always stay long term in each city/country in order to save the apartment cost, that's does not only affect our budget in a positive way but it also helps us travel more, understand and immerse ourself into the culture of each city/country better also. 

FIXED COST 

1. Rental ( Chiangmai ) : we rent apartment at The Trio, Huay Kaew. It is closed to Maya Mall. You can also look into more detail from this video : https://youtu.be/y4CLRf8-0vY

2. Motorbike ( Chiangmai ) We rent motorbike from Mango bike rent, it is the cheapest we could find in December,2017 it cost us 2,500 / month / motorbike You can also look into more detail from their website  : http://www.mangobikesrent.com 

3. Home Internet - we get the service from 3BB, the reason why is because our landloard suggest us this service provider. Besides 3BB, another famous home internet provider in Thailand is TRUE

4. Mobile data : We get the service from TRUE, Besides TRUE, another famous mobile data provider is DTAC and AIS


VARIABLE COST : 

Transportation 
- sky train : find out the route and timetable here : http://www.bts.co.th/customer/en/02-route-current_new.aspx
- Bus : http://www.bmta.co.th/?q=en/services
- Airport rail link : http://www.srtet.co.th/index.php/en/information-ticket

MOBILE TOP UP
- We top up the money at 7-11 and sometimes from Boonterm machine

FOOD
- We cook most of the time, and where we love doing grocery is TESCO LOTUS as the meat and bakery there is cheap and vegetables at times got the discount up to 70%

__________________________________________________________

SUBSCRIBE FOR ( ALMOST ) DAILY TRAVEL VLOG :D

https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCO-BUJCM03NS-rwr1VonV4A?sub_confirmation=1

___________________________________________________________

Check out our previous VLOG if you missed :  EXPLORING CEBU | WHALE SHARKS OF OSLOB, TUMALOG WATERFALL, PHILIPPINES TRAVEL VLOG 2018 |

here is the link : https://youtu.be/WIuRD7njj0Y

_________________________________________________

let's chat guys, we are really happy to see you guys comment on our channel and that really means the world to us.

Instagram : divertliving

title: Rohingya babies dumped and left to die | Hotspots
tags: Sky News|skynews|news|War zone|conflict|Myanmar|Aung San Suu Kyi|Burma|Rohingya|Refugee|Refugee camp|Refugee crisis|Rahkine|Bangladesh|Nobel Peace Prize|nobel prize|violence|human rights|human rights abuse|genocide|refugee crisis|muslim|islam
description:
Sky News's Alex Crawford was the first to uncover independent evidence from Myanmar's Rakhine State which laid bare the shocking deprivation and desperation among thousands of stranded Rohingya Muslims.

The alarming footage shows emaciated women and newborn babies who were dumped on beaches and left to die - just some of the victims of Myanmar's brutal crackdown against the Rohingyas.

Watch the truly alarming footage as Alex explains what it was like to film

title: AMAZING COCONUT FACTORY CHIANG RAI THAILAND ‚ù§Ô∏èÔ∏è
tags: Coconuts|proccessing|Opening coconut|how to|where do coconuts come from|Thailand|Chiang Rai|coconut|machette|Drinking coconut|coconut water|supplier|factory|hotel|holiday|thai fruit|street food|thailand|thai|fruit ninja|cut|cutting
description:
Ever wondered how the thirst quenching drinking coconuts of Thailand are processed? I visited a coconut supplier in Chiang Rai  to see how its done and was very impressed with the knife skills of the workers. Here the young drinking coconuts are delivered by truck from the south as its a little cold to grow vast amounts of coconuts in Chiang Rai. 

They are hand processed in 2 ways, first is cut  and shaped so they sit flat and easy to open with a machete. Second is all the husk removed to present the coconut itself. If you have drinking coconuts in Chiang Rai, this is where they come from.

 It's amazing how the taste varies with species and age. I find the young coconuts fresh from the tree irresistible. Thanks for watching and please subscribe if you would like to see more videos. Please hit the like and subscribe button if you would be so kind to support my channel, thanks so much. This video is Copyright

title: Siam Park City - Bangkok's LARGEST Amusement/Water park!
tags: Thailand|Bangkok|Bangkok Thailand|Siam Park City|Siam Park City Waterpark|Siam Park City Amusement Park|Siam Park City is Bangkok's largest amusement and water park|Siam Park Bangkok|Bangkok Amusement Parks|Thailand Tourism|Suvarnabhumi International Airport|Waterpark|Amusement Park|Guinness World Records|Destination Thailand|Capital TV Bangkok|Thai Waterpark|siam park wave pool|bangkok things to do|rollercoaster|travel|adrenaline|attraction
description:
A great escape from Bangkok only 20 minutes from Suvarnabhumi International Airport. Opened in 1980 under the name of "Suansiam" it was the first waterpark in Thailand with it's own man-made beach. It now boasts seven attractions including a huge wave pool certified as the world's largest by the Guinness World Records since 2009.  The amusement park section offers a choice of almost 40 rides including its world-class Vortex roller-coaster and the Giant Drop, a free fall ride.

Siam Park City: Bangkok's LARGEST Amusement/water park!

title: TRAVEL VIDEO | Thailand Lantern Festival Yi Peng | Chiang Mai
tags: travel video|onceuponajrny|once upon a journey|lesbian travel|travel vlog|travel blog|travel instagram|chiang mai|yi peng|yee peng|thailand|lantern festival|light festival|lantern|world trip|southeast asia|asia|rox & maartje|roxanne & maartje|lights|lanterns|loi krathong|loy krathong|tangled|see the light|at last i see the light|i see the light|disney|wish balloons|balloon|wish balloon
description:
Yi Peng is the Thailand lantern festival in Chiang Mai: the biggest celebration takes place in Chiang Mai. Yi Peng is celebrated on the first day of Loy Krathong; a light festival that is celebrated in Thailand and surrounding countries. The celebration takes place on the full moon of the twelfth lunar month every year. 
__

Read everything about the festival in our Ultimate Guide to the Yi Peng lantern festival ‚úé https://onceuponajrny.com/destinations/asia/thailand/yi-peng-lantern-festival-chiang-mai/

title: EXOTIC PETS AT CHATUCHAK WEEKEND MARKET IN BANGKOK,  WET MARKET IN THAILAND,
tags: EXOTIC PETS|BANGKOK|PET SHOP|EXOTIC PETS SHOP|BANGKOK 2017|BANGKOK SHOPPING|PET SHOP BANGKOK|CHATUCHAK MARKET|CHATUCHAK MARKET BANGKOK|JJ MARKET|JJ MARKET BANGKOK|THE BIGGEST MARKET IN THE WORLD|BANGKOK MARKET|WEEKEND MARKET BANGKOK|PUPPIES|DOGS|SHOPPING|CUTE|PETS|PET|WET MARKET|ASIA WET MARKET|BANGKOK WET MARKET
description:
EXOTIC PETS AT CHATUCHAK WEEKEND MARKET IN BANGKOK,  WET MARKET IN THAILAND, Chatuchak Market: Home of the World's Largest Weekend Market, The Chatuchak Weekend Market (Thai: ‡∏ï‡∏•‡∏≤‡∏î‡∏ô‡∏±‡∏î‡∏à‡∏ï‡∏∏‡∏à‡∏±‡∏Å‡∏£), on Kamphaeng Phet 2 Road, Chatuchak, Bangkok, is the largest market in Thailand.[1] Also known as JJ Market, it has more than 8,000 stalls, divided into 27 sections. Chatuchak Market sells nine kinds of goods: plants, antiques, pets, food and drinks, fresh and dry food, ceramics, furniture and home decor, clothing, and books. Chatuchak Market has been open since 1942.[3] In 1948, when Prime Minister Jompol Por Pibulsongkraam had a policy in which every province was required to have their own market. Bangkok chose Sanam Luang to be held as the market. After a few months, the government had to move the market to Sanam Chai, but the market moved back to Sanam Luang in 1958. In 1978, the government used Sanam Luang as a recreational area, so the State Railway of Thailand donated the land on the south side of Chatuchak Park to establish as a market. By 1983, all of the merchants had moved to Chatuchak. At that time the market was called Phahonyothin Market. In 1987, its name was changed to Chatuchak Market.[4]

Trade in illegal wildlife[edit]
Studies have shown that the Chatuchuk Market is a centre for trade in illegal wildlife.[5][6]

In a survey conducted on 28‚Äì29 March 2015, researchers counted 1,271 birds of 117 species for sale in 45 shops or stalls. Of the total, nine species were listed as "Threatened" on the IUCN Red List and eight species as "Near Threatened".[5]:24-29[7]

Clock tower[edit]
The clock tower is a distinctive landmark in the Chatuchuk Market. It was built in 1987 on the occasion of King Bhumibol Adulyadej's 60th birthday on 5 December 1987, a cooperative effort of the market administration and Thai-Chinese Merchant Association.[citation needed]

Market sections[edit]
Clothing and accessories (sections 2‚Äì6, 10‚Äì26)
Handicrafts (sections 8‚Äì11)
Ceramics (sections 11, 13, 15, 17, 19, 25)
Furniture and home decor (sections 1,3,4,7,8)
Food and beverage (sections 2, 3, 4, 23, 24, 26, 27)
Plants and gardening (sections 3, 4)
Art and galleries (section 7)
Pets and accessories (sections 8, 9, 11, 13)
Books (sections 1, 27)
Antiques and collectibles (sections 1, 26)
Miscellaneous and used clothing (sections 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 22, 25, 26)[2]
Nearby Place[edit]
Chatuchak Weekend Market is located near some popular places, for example JJ green market, Mo Chit BTS Station, Chatuchak Park MRT Station and Chatuchak Park. This market is a place where you can easily connect to other places by using BTS and MRT. Chatuchak market is open during the day. However, there are other nearby markets open at night time, such as JJ green market. You can also rest or picnic at Chatuchak Park.

title: Inside Myanmar: The Crackdown l Rewind
tags: aljazeera|aljazeera english|al jazeera english|al jazeera|al jazeera live|government crackdown|protesting monks|burma|birtley|violence|yangon|rohingya|bangladesh|aung san suu kyi|myanmar protest|rohingya genocide|rohingya muslims|myanmar rohingya|myanmar rohingya crisis|british burma|burma history|aljazeera live|myanmar military|myanmar|thanakha|mohinga|chinatown|sule pagoda|rangoon|burmese|junction city|junction square|junction mall|burmania|burmia|burmes
description:
From Inside Myanmar 2007, the people of Myanmar were still living under harsh military rule. Among the first major international news stories Al Jazeera covered was the Myanmar government's brutal crackdown on peacefully protesting monks. 

News reaching the outside world at that time was scarce. But Al Jazeera correspondent Tony Birtley was one of the few international journalists who had managed to get into the country, and was able to film the unfolding events while working undercover at the very heart of the protests.

From the archives, originally published in 2007. Link to original video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1UqQaizM15Q

title: S1 E13 #FreedomCamping in Penang and Jitra #Vanlife MALAYSIA
tags: Van Life|Van Build|Tourism Malaysia|Campervan|Caravan|Self Built|Malaysia|Travel|Thailand|Indonesia|Overland|Adventure|Penang|Kedah|Toyota Liteace|DIY Camper|stealth camping|camping
description:
We went #FREEDOMCAMPING #WILDCAMPING IN PENANG & JITRA no fees required. 

We meet a fellow campervan owner in Penang named Farid, he takes us to his hometown in Jitra Kedah near the border of Thailand. We end up going on an epic adventure from KL to Penang to Jitra to Cameron Highlands to KKB and back to KL in 5 days all by travelling and living in our campervan.

WHO WE ARE - 

Rene is a Musician from Singapore and Sam is a Photographer from Malaysia. In April 2017, we decided to minimise and simplify life. Time had passed us by and we now knew we needed a change. We began selling our possessions (still in the middle of selling) bought a Toyota Liteace Premio 1.8 1995 and self converted a into a tiny campervan in order to travel with our dogs Roxy and Bo. To get used to this new change, we decided to start our travels within Malaysia with an end goal of one day driving overland from Malaysia to the UK.

We share our experiences with Campervan Builds, Travel Adventures and Interviews of People who inspire us -  we provide access to information for those who may want to do the same one day.  

HOW DO WE SUPPORT OUR NEW JOURNEY?

This doesn't have one simple answer. For the transition period we purely operate on savings as we build our means to earn money on the road. We need stacking income - in Bahasa Malaysia there is saying, "Sikit Sikit Jadi Bukit" and that's what we are trying to develop. 

DROP US A MESSAGE, LIKE COMMENT SHARE AND SUBSCRIBE maybe we can meet up someday?

Cheers, 
Sam & Rene

title: Sapphire mining around Chanthaburi (Thailand)
description:
Dear all, I'm happy to invite you to discover the most recent field video on my new YouTube Channel: 
This time, I'm going to take you to discover sapphire mining around Chanthaburi in Thailand: Since the early 2000, the areas around Khao Ploy Wen volcano and Ban Ka Cha village have become one of the world most active sapphire mining areas producing mainly black star and yellow sapphires. The video was done in March 2017 and for the first time in that area we had a drone to help us getting images of the mining. Thanks to my team for that expedition: My field cameramen: Didier Barriere and Anthony Methez from Nomad's Media and Nomads Drone and my team mates: Justin K Prim, Myriam Buduca, Alexey Spirit Yakhlakov and Kim Rix.

title: Ko Phi Phi Le Island, Thailand | Phi Phi Island, Maya Bay, Pileh Lagoon, Viking Cave | Phuket, Krabi
tags: ko phi phi le|ko phi phi le island|phi phi le island|phi phi|phi phi island|things to do in thailand|things to do in phuket|things to do in krabi|things to do in phi phi|things to do in phi phi island|maya bay|how to get to maya bay|how to get to phi phi island|snorkeling maya bay|pileh lagoon|longtail boat to maya bay|the beach maya bay|getting to maya bay|longtail boats thailand|viking cave|getting to phi phi island
description:
This review is for those travelers looking to check out Ko Phi Phi Le (including Maya Bay and Pileh Lagoon), just outside Phi Phi Island in Thailand. We traveled there while we were staying in Phuket, but there are a few routes that can be taken to get there as well from Krabi or other local places. 

*Watch out full Thailand vacation video here: https://youtu.be/E116KQQ5C7Y

You can only get to Phi Phi Island by boat.  Coming from Phuket, it's around 1000 Baht for a roundtrip ticket and about a 1 ¬Ω to 2 hour boat ride to Phi Phi.  Boats leave only a few times throughout the day with the earliest ferry leaving Phuket at 8:30am and heading back from Phi Phi at 2:30pm so if you are making a day trip there without staying the night, you will have only around 4-5 hours at most on the Island. 

On the boat over there are food and drink available for purchase (including local beers).  Cash only.  The boat has seating up on the top deck which is open, or on the middle and lower levels which are covered.  Getting to the dock earlier will ensure that you get a good seat. 

While there are many things to do on Phi Phi, many choose to venture to Ko Phi Phi Lee. You can do a group tour via speed boat, which is typically with 20-30 other people, not very fun.  Or you can get a more authentic and private tour on a longtail boat. Upon arrival in Phi Phi, you‚Äôll be met by several longtail boat drivers willing to take you to the island for around 2000 Baht. Definitely worth the extra money.  We went with a group of 4 of us and there was plenty of room, they stop where you want to and its so much more enjoyable than a speed boat. 

*If you have back problems or get motion sickness, the longtail boats can be difficult when the waters are rough being very bumpy. 

Its a nice ride over to Ko Phi Phi Le, about 20-30 minutes.  The popular things to do once  Ko Phi Phi Le is to visit Maya Bay, which was made famous by Leonardo DiCaprio in the movie The Beach. We recommend going early in the morning to beat the crowds otherwise it'll be way overcrowded with hundreds of other people.  If you choose to stop at Maya Bay beach, there is a 400 Baht entrance fee to get onto the beach. 

The next stop we recommend is at Pileh lagoon which is very scenic and a bit more low key compared to Maya bay while allows for a more privacy and seclusion.  Our longtail boat driver pulled into a small beach area where we were the only ones for about 30 minutes where we were able to enjoy snorkeling and swimming in the gorgeous waters of the Lagoon.  

The trip back to Phi Phi Island is very scenic as you will be passing several great photo opportunities, coves and Pirate Cave which is popular with the tourists. 

Once back on Phi Phi Island, you probably only have a short amount of time left before the ferry departs (probably less than an hour).  Use this time to explore the local shops and restaurants or head to the other side of Phi Phi Island to Loh Delum Beach to relax before boarding the ferry back to Phuket.  You can walk at least 100 years at Loh Delum beach and still be able to stand.  

Hope this video helps plan your next trip to Phi Phi Island/Ko Phi Phi Le Island.  Don't forget hit subscribe and thanks for watching.

description:
VIETNAM MOTORCYCLE TRIP - Ho Chi Minh to Hanoi & Ha Long Bay

We completed this trip in Motorbike trip through Vietnam from December-January 2015-2016. After loving our experience traveling Vietnam so much, we went back to do it again! You can check out the second trip another epic video... with higher quality cameras here:

NORTHERN LOOP MOTORBIKE TRIP (HA GIANG)

ON THE BLOG
https://www.timandfintravel.com

HOW TO PLAN YOUR AROUND THE WORLD ITINERARY (+ FREE DOWNLOAD)
https://www.timandfintravel.com/blog/... 

HOW TO SAVE ENOUGH MONEY IN ONE YEAR TO TRAVEL (+ FREE DOWNLOAD)
https://www.timandfintravel.com/blog/...

-----------------

MUSIC IN THIS EPISODE:
http://bit.ly/timfinepidemic
     
-----------    
LET'S BE FRIENDS:
     INSTAGRAM: http://instagram.com/timandfin
     FACEBOOK: http://facebook.com/timandfin
     PATREON: https://www.patreon.com/timandfin

Can‚Äôt thank you enough for being here and checking out our channel!  Please drop a line any time either in the comments or at hello@timandfintravel.com
Seeing the Top Gear Vietnam special only further increased the anticipation for one day taking part in it myself. If you‚Äôre looking how to motorbike Vietnam, the routes to take, the type of motorbike to take, and top things to do in each location, this video will help!
What‚Äôs the first thing anyone would need on a Vietnam motorcycle trip? Motorbikes of course! After touching down in Saigon that's the first "to-do" item we tackled.  While I had long dreamed of making the trip on a proper motorcycle it simply wasn't to be. 

The motorbikes that backpackers typically buy are notoriously unreliable.  While a few breakdowns might be funny, the group decided to rent so we could maximize the fun part of our trip.  We chose to rent more reliable brand new motorbikes from Tigit in Saigon. From a safety and reliability standpoint, Tigit rentals are far better than the Chinese knock off Honda Wins that can be found in backpacker quarters for sale around the city.
Vietnam Motorbike Trip Distance and Prep
The distance that we'll be driving on this Vietnam motorcycle trip is the equivalent of riding from Key West to Chicago. That's over 2,400 kms.  We'll be joined for the first two weeks by two travel companions. 
Before heading out on the open road the group also does a bit of shopping to prepare for the journey ahead. Vietnamese roads are a bit crazy with all of the motorcycle traffic so helmets and proper clothing are necessary. Allison opts for a helmet, kneepads, and elbow pads because she‚Äôs careful. Jaime goes with rolled up sleeves, an unbuckled helmet and flipflops because he is about two steps out of the trailer park.

------------

ABOUT US:
We‚Äôre traveling full time, living on our own terms and showing you the up-close-and-personal details of us figuring it out along the way. Sometimes it‚Äôs about navigating big, life-altering decisions. Sometimes it‚Äôs about navigating the seemingly lawless free-for-all that is driving in Hanoi. It‚Äôs moments of triumph and moments of panic. The good, the bad, the ugly ‚Äì and most importantly, the real and real funny.

We‚Äôre not here to tell you ‚Äúhow it‚Äôs done.‚Äù Just how we‚Äôve done it. And that whatever it is that‚Äôs calling you - the way you‚Äôll do it is much more attainable than it may seem. We believe the world‚Äôs a more interesting place when people reject convention in favor of what they actually care about. This is us putting that idea to the test ‚Äì one budget spreadsheet, RV renovation and mountain-peak drone video at a time.

title: Caviar Production - Sturgeon Farm based in Hua Hin Thailand
tags: Thailand|Hua Hin|Caviar|Caviar Sturgeon Farm|Caviar production in Thailand's Sturgeon Farm based in Hua Hin|Fish farms in Thailand|Sturgeon Thailand|Sturgeon Hua Hin|Hua Hin business enterprises|Caviar House|Destination Thailand|Sturgeon fish breeding in Hua Hin|Sturgeon fish breeding in Thailand|Caviar production in the tropics|caviar thailand|living in thailand|thai food|thailand vlogs|Farm|Thailand entrepreneur|Fish Farming|Fish|Hua Hin Thailand|Sturgeon
description:
Alexey and Noppadorn are the faces behind the importation of Caviar  in Thailand under their "Caviar House" enterprise brand. They are regularly seen promoting their delicacy at swanky high-end social events throughout Thailand. Their latest venture is the opening of a high-tech fish farm with the purpose of producing caviar, sturgeon meat and value-added products for both the national and international markets. Based in Hua Hin, the first phase facility of 1,500 square meters was built for a production capacity of 1,500 kg of black caviar per year. 
www.sturgeon.co.th

description:
How To Make Thai Holy Basil Chicken Stir Fry | Pad Ka Prao Gai | Authentic Family Recipe #12
Amy from World of Thai Food present how to make a "Pad Ka Prao Gai‚Äù recipe that has been passed down in her Thai family over generations. This is authentic Thai home cooking at its best and easiest.

Spelling of Thai words in English is ambiguous and there is little or no official standardisation. Thai Holy Basil stir fry is commonly referred to as Pad Ka Prao, Pad Ka-Prao, Pad Kra Pao, Pad Kra Prao, Pad Ga Prao, Pad Ga-Prao, Pad Gaprao, Pad Krapow

Recipe: Thai Holy Basil Chicken - Pad Ka Prao Gai.

Serves: 4

Ingredients:
300 g Chicken (minced)
1 cup Thai Holy Basil leaves
15 cloves of Garlic
7 Bird's Eye Chili
3 tbsp Oyster sauce
2 tbsp Seasoning soy sauce

1 tbsp Palm sugar

title: Finalmente al Mare - Koh Samui - Vacanza in Thailandia 2017 - Travel Vlog #4 üáπüá≠
tags: koh samui vlog|koh samui giada|koh samui estate 2017|kho samui|ko samui|koh samui|kosamui|mare koh samui|i posti piu belli di koh samui|cosa fare a koh samui|koh samui 2017|cosa vedere a koh samui|koh samui cosa vedere|thailandia koh samui|koh samui spiagge|koh samui thailand|koh samui ita|koh samui thailandia|samui|vacanza in thailandia|giadamilleesperienze|mare thailandia|thailandia mare|giada mille esperienze|vlog thailandia|viaggio in thailandia
description:
Finalmente al mare! Koh Samui - Vacanza in Thailandia 2017 - Travel Vlog #4

La vacanza prosegue e da Chiang Mai prendiamo un volo Thai Airways fino a Bangkok.
Qui, dopo un paio d'ore di scalo, ci imbarchiamo su un aereo ad eliche per arrivare a Koh Samui.

Oltre ad avere uno degli aeroporti pi√π belli del mondo, Koh Samui offre una moltitudine di cose da fare, dalla visita alle spiagge alle cascate.
Il resort dove abbiamo soggiornato si chiama Baan Talay Resort, √® situato nella parte sud di Chaweng in riva al mare!

In questo primo giorno, con il nostro scooter, da Chaweng ci dirigiamo verso sud e ci fermiamo alla spiaggia di Silver Beach. Poi visitiamo la spiaggia di Hin Ta & Hin Yai famosa per le rocce a forma di genitali.
Dopo pranzo visitiamo la cascata di Wan Sao Thong ed infine ci fermiamo alla spiaggia vicino a Koh Na Thian, dalle parti del Samui Aquarium & Tiger Zoo. 
La sera facciamo un giro in centro a Chaweng.

Esplorate l'isola insieme a noi!

description:
How To Make Jim Jaew - Spicy Thai BBQ Dipping Sauce | Condiment & Sauce Guide #3
Amy from World of Thai Food present how to make Nam Jim Jaew - A simple and delicious Barbecue Dipping Sauce served with grilled dishes. This is authentic Thai home cooking at its best and easiest.

We began uploading our first series of Thai Family Recipes and our Condiment & Sauce Guide on the 16th of June 2017 and this is our 9th published video. You can expect many more to come over the next weeks as we complete post production of our content.

Our website will go live soon and at that point we will add the links to it here - that's where you will find our recipes. In the meantime we will publish the recipe below just in case some of you might want to try it out!

World of Thai Food on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/worldofthaifood/
World of Thai Food on Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/worldofthaifood/
World of Thai Food on Pinterest: https://www.pinterest.se/worldofthaifood/pins/

Recipe: Nam Jim Jaew - Thai Spicy BBQ dipping sauce

Fish Sauce          4 tbsp
Lime Juice          2 tbsp
Tamarind Puree 2 tbsp
Palm Sugar         1 ¬Ω tbsp
Dried Chili flakes  1 ¬Ω tbsp
Roasted Rice Powder  1 ¬Ω tbsp
Shallots               2 thinly sliced or chopped as per preference
Coriander            2-3 twigs chopped
Spring Onion      1-2 chopped

description:
How To Make Prik Nam Pla - Thai Table Sauce | Condiment & Sauce Guide #2
Amy from World of Thai Food present how to make Prik Nam Pla - A Table Condiment that is served with almost every dish. This is authentic Thai home cooking at its best and easiest.

Our website will go live soon and at that point we will add the links to it here - that's where you will find our recipes.

World of Thai Food on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/worldofthaifood/
World of Thai Food on Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/worldofthaifood/
World of Thai Food on Pinterest: https://www.pinterest.se/worldofthaifood/pins/

Recipe: Prik Nam Pla (4 servings)

4 tbsp Fish Sauce
2 tbsp Lime juice
3-4 Bird‚Äôs eye chillies (thinly sliced)
1 shallot (halved and thinly sliced)

Start by slicing shallot and chilies finely. Add 4 tbsp of fish sauce and 2 tbsp of lime juice in a bowl (the ratio is 2:1). Stir and then add the finely sliced shallots and chillies.
Serve directly.

Art Thomya, a Thai singer/songwriter, will show you the 7 Must-Sees in KRABI, a Southern Thai province by The Andaman, globally famous for its stunningly beautiful nature. title: Pattaya with Kids | Pattaya Thailand | Top things to do with kids
tags: Pattaya For Kids|What To Do In Pattaya|vrindas adventures|Pattaya Holidays|Thailand|Pattaya Attractions|Weekend In Pattaya|Must See Pattaya|Pattaya for family|Travel Guide|Travel Tips|Kids Travel|Family trip to Pattaya|Best of Pattaya|Vrinda|pattaya with kids|pattaya with family|parasailing|koh larn|mercure pattaya ocean resort|thai masaage|Family Travel|top attractions|Water Park|Mercure|travel|thailand|things to do in pattaya|pattaya
description:
My Top 5 tips on Pattaya, Thailand. These are the things that *kids* will enjoy in Pattaya. It's a beautiful city that offers lots of fun activities for families.


1. Koh Larn: For water sports like para sailing, body surfing, jet ski etc and great food.
2. Alcazar Show: Beautiful musical and dance show
3. Mercure Pattaya Ocean Resort: Amazing place for stay as it has it's own water park!
4. Traditional Thai Massage: Must for anyone visiting Thailand
5. Food - Crepe, Chicken Satay, Mango with Sticky rice

description:
From Inside Myanmar 2007, the people of Myanmar were still living under harsh military rule. Among the first major international news stories Al Jazeera covered was the Myanmar government's brutal crackdown on peacefully protesting monks. 

News reaching the outside world at that time was scarce. But Al Jazeera correspondent Tony Birtley was one of the few international journalists who had managed to get into the country, and was able to film the unfolding events while working undercover at the very heart of the protests.

From the archives, originally published in 2007. Link to original video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1UqQaizM15Q

title: S1 E13 #FreedomCamping in Penang and Jitra #Vanlife MALAYSIA
tags: Van Life|Van Build|Tourism Malaysia|Campervan|Caravan|Self Built|Malaysia|Travel|Thailand|Indonesia|Overland|Adventure|Penang|Kedah|Toyota Liteace|DIY Camper|stealth camping|camping
description:
We went #FREEDOMCAMPING #WILDCAMPING IN PENANG & JITRA no fees required. 

We meet a fellow campervan owner in Penang named Farid, he takes us to his hometown in Jitra Kedah near the border of Thailand. We end up going on an epic adventure from KL to Penang to Jitra to Cameron Highlands to KKB and back to KL in 5 days all by travelling and living in our campervan.

WHO WE ARE - 

Rene is a Musician from Singapore and Sam is a Photographer from Malaysia. In April 2017, we decided to minimise and simplify life. Time had passed us by and we now knew we needed a change. We began selling our possessions (still in the middle of selling) bought a Toyota Liteace Premio 1.8 1995 and self converted a into a tiny campervan in order to travel with our dogs Roxy and Bo. To get used to this new change, we decided to start our travels within Malaysia with an end goal of one day driving overland from Malaysia to the UK.

We share our experiences with Campervan Builds, Travel Adventures and Interviews of People who inspire us -  we provide access to information for those who may want to do the same one day.  

HOW DO WE SUPPORT OUR NEW JOURNEY?

This doesn't have one simple answer. For the transition period we purely operate on savings as we build our means to earn money on the road. We need stacking income - in Bahasa Malaysia there is saying, "Sikit Sikit Jadi Bukit" and that's what we are trying to develop. 

DROP US A MESSAGE, LIKE COMMENT SHARE AND SUBSCRIBE maybe we can meet up someday?

Cheers, 
Sam & Rene

title: Sapphire mining around Chanthaburi (Thailand)
description:
Dear all, I'm happy to invite you to discover the most recent field video on my new YouTube Channel: 
This time, I'm going to take you to discover sapphire mining around Chanthaburi in Thailand: Since the early 2000, the areas around Khao Ploy Wen volcano and Ban Ka Cha village have become one of the world most active sapphire mining areas producing mainly black star and yellow sapphires. The video was done in March 2017 and for the first time in that area we had a drone to help us getting images of the mining. Thanks to my team for that expedition: My field cameramen: Didier Barriere and Anthony Methez from Nomad's Media and Nomads Drone and my team mates: Justin K Prim, Myriam Buduca, Alexey Spirit Yakhlakov and Kim Rix.

title: Ko Phi Phi Le Island, Thailand | Phi Phi Island, Maya Bay, Pileh Lagoon, Viking Cave | Phuket, Krabi
tags: ko phi phi le|ko phi phi le island|phi phi le island|phi phi|phi phi island|things to do in thailand|things to do in phuket|things to do in krabi|things to do in phi phi|things to do in phi phi island|maya bay|how to get to maya bay|how to get to phi phi island|snorkeling maya bay|pileh lagoon|longtail boat to maya bay|the beach maya bay|getting to maya bay|longtail boats thailand|viking cave|getting to phi phi island
description:
This review is for those travelers looking to check out Ko Phi Phi Le (including Maya Bay and Pileh Lagoon), just outside Phi Phi Island in Thailand. We traveled there while we were staying in Phuket, but there are a few routes that can be taken to get there as well from Krabi or other local places. 

*Watch out full Thailand vacation video here: https://youtu.be/E116KQQ5C7Y

You can only get to Phi Phi Island by boat.  Coming from Phuket, it's around 1000 Baht for a roundtrip ticket and about a 1 ¬Ω to 2 hour boat ride to Phi Phi.  Boats leave only a few times throughout the day with the earliest ferry leaving Phuket at 8:30am and heading back from Phi Phi at 2:30pm so if you are making a day trip there without staying the night, you will have only around 4-5 hours at most on the Island. 

On the boat over there are food and drink available for purchase (including local beers).  Cash only.  The boat has seating up on the top deck which is open, or on the middle and lower levels which are covered.  Getting to the dock earlier will ensure that you get a good seat. 

While there are many things to do on Phi Phi, many choose to venture to Ko Phi Phi Lee. You can do a group tour via speed boat, which is typically with 20-30 other people, not very fun.  Or you can get a more authentic and private tour on a longtail boat. Upon arrival in Phi Phi, you‚Äôll be met by several longtail boat drivers willing to take you to the island for around 2000 Baht. Definitely worth the extra money.  We went with a group of 4 of us and there was plenty of room, they stop where you want to and its so much more enjoyable than a speed boat. 

*If you have back problems or get motion sickness, the longtail boats can be difficult when the waters are rough being very bumpy. 

Its a nice ride over to Ko Phi Phi Le, about 20-30 minutes.  The popular things to do once  Ko Phi Phi Le is to visit Maya Bay, which was made famous by Leonardo DiCaprio in the movie The Beach. We recommend going early in the morning to beat the crowds otherwise it'll be way overcrowded with hundreds of other people.  If you choose to stop at Maya Bay beach, there is a 400 Baht entrance fee to get onto the beach. 

The next stop we recommend is at Pileh lagoon which is very scenic and a bit more low key compared to Maya bay while allows for a more privacy and seclusion.  Our longtail boat driver pulled into a small beach area where we were the only ones for about 30 minutes where we were able to enjoy snorkeling and swimming in the gorgeous waters of the Lagoon.  

The trip back to Phi Phi Island is very scenic as you will be passing several great photo opportunities, coves and Pirate Cave which is popular with the tourists. 

Once back on Phi Phi Island, you probably only have a short amount of time left before the ferry departs (probably less than an hour).  Use this time to explore the local shops and restaurants or head to the other side of Phi Phi Island to Loh Delum Beach to relax before boarding the ferry back to Phuket.  You can walk at least 100 years at Loh Delum beach and still be able to stand.  

Hope this video helps plan your next trip to Phi Phi Island/Ko Phi Phi Le Island.  Don't forget hit subscribe and thanks for watching.

Can‚Äôt thank you enough for being here and checking out our channel!  Please drop a line any time either in the comments or at hello@timandfintravel.com
Seeing the Top Gear Vietnam special only further increased the anticipation for one day taking part in it myself. If you‚Äôre looking how to motorbike Vietnam, the routes to take, the type of motorbike to take, and top things to do in each location, this video will help!
What‚Äôs the first thing anyone would need on a Vietnam motorcycle trip? Motorbikes of course! After touching down in Saigon that's the first "to-do" item we tackled.  While I had long dreamed of making the trip on a proper motorcycle it simply wasn't to be. 

The motorbikes that backpackers typically buy are notoriously unreliable.  While a few breakdowns might be funny, the group decided to rent so we could maximize the fun part of our trip.  We chose to rent more reliable brand new motorbikes from Tigit in Saigon. From a safety and reliability standpoint, Tigit rentals are far better than the Chinese knock off Honda Wins that can be found in backpacker quarters for sale around the city.
Vietnam Motorbike Trip Distance and Prep
The distance that we'll be driving on this Vietnam motorcycle trip is the equivalent of riding from Key West to Chicago. That's over 2,400 kms.  We'll be joined for the first two weeks by two travel companions. 
Before heading out on the open road the group also does a bit of shopping to prepare for the journey ahead. Vietnamese roads are a bit crazy with all of the motorcycle traffic so helmets and proper clothing are necessary. Allison opts for a helmet, kneepads, and elbow pads because she‚Äôs careful. Jaime goes with rolled up sleeves, an unbuckled helmet and flipflops because he is about two steps out of the trailer park.

------------

ABOUT US:
We‚Äôre traveling full time, living on our own terms and showing you the up-close-and-personal details of us figuring it out along the way. Sometimes it‚Äôs about navigating big, life-altering decisions. Sometimes it‚Äôs about navigating the seemingly lawless free-for-all that is driving in Hanoi. It‚Äôs moments of triumph and moments of panic. The good, the bad, the ugly ‚Äì and most importantly, the real and real funny.

We‚Äôre not here to tell you ‚Äúhow it‚Äôs done.‚Äù Just how we‚Äôve done it. And that whatever it is that‚Äôs calling you - the way you‚Äôll do it is much more attainable than it may seem. We believe the world‚Äôs a more interesting place when people reject convention in favor of what they actually care about. This is us putting that idea to the test ‚Äì one budget spreadsheet, RV renovation and mountain-peak drone video at a time.

title: üîÖ Tropical White Sand Beach with the Sound of Soothing Ocean Waves for Sleeping or Relaxation Enjoy!
tags: beach|tropical|ocean|sea|waves|ambience|relaxation|sleeping|soundscape|palmtree|beach view|white sand|paradise beach|Ngwe Saung|Myanmar|waves hitting the shore|quiet beach|beach scenery|relaxing ambience|waves crashing|relaxing soundzzz|calming and relaxing
description:
Beautiful tropical paradise beach recorded on Ngwe Saung Beach (Myanmar). Enjoy this soothing soundscape video with a beautiful view of the sea and beach. This relaxing beach scenery is combined with the sound of gentle ocean waves hitting the shore and is made for relaxation or sleeping. Ngwe Saung is a nice 15 kilometers long and quiet beach, maybe this is the place you would like to go this or next summer? Let us know in a message!

‚óº All my soundscape videos are made in high quality with editing programs such as Vegas Pro, Photoshop and Audacity, and take many hours / days of editing and mixing to create. The equipment I use to record the audio are the Zoom H5 or H6 recorder + Audio-Technica BP4025 microphone, and for the videos I use the GoPro Hero6. Some video and audio files are made in collaboration with other video / audio creators with all the licenses & commercial use rights that are necessary. I mixed these video or audio files with the creation of myself. Sometimes I use a photo and make a moving video of it. 
See this photo as an example: https://pixabay.com/nl/photos/sneeuw-sunrise-boom-park-winter-2010710/  
Watch the video I made of this photo: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ba0VaEIEO6U

title: Perhentian Islands | MALAYSIA, Terengganu | Let's Travel #9
description:
We stayed one week at this amazing place. It was by far one of our favourite places. 
The resort was incredible! Almost no people! Amazing beach with warm transparent water. A lot of different animals (monkeys jumping around on the top of the trees, big lizards, baby sharks, etc.)

I loved it and would return there in a heart beat!

description:
TheVibe Originals - Tune into Away From Home | Discovering the Andaman Islands on June 8, 2016 World Oceans Day; 

Episode 3 :   Tara and Rohan leaving in a convoy from Jirkatang as they travel through the Jarawa Tribal Reserve, where photography is strictly forbidden. They head to Mayabunder to John's Homestay. John introduces the travellers to the "Karen" culture and its people. Karens are the largest ethnic tribe in Burma and were brought to the Andaman Islands from Burma by the British in 1925. The travellers then make their way to the Avis Island, where Tara goes free diving in its tropical waters.

title: Away From Home | Discovering the Andaman Islands : Episode 1
tags: TheVibe|The Vibe|TheVibe Originals|The Vibe Originals|Away From Home|Way Back Home|Way Back Home 2|Travel|Adventure|Culture|Lifestyle|Andamans|Andaman Islands|rohan thakur|Rohan Thakur|Tara Jain|Nayantara Jain|tara jain|World Oceans Day|Oceans|Incredible India|Action|Little Andamans|People|ANET
description:
Away From Home | Discovering the Andaman Islands | Way Back Home - Chapter II, on June 8, 2016 World Oceans Day, as part of TheVibeOriginals.

In the Second Chapter of Way Back Home titled Away From Home: Discovering the Andaman Islands, filmmaker Rohan Thakur teams up with coral reef researcher Nayantara Jain to explore the Andaman Islands of India. 

The series walks through an immersive experience, soaking in the sights, sounds and activities of the local Andamanis. Way Back Home is a first-of-its-kind travelogue on India as it trails young, authentic, passionate travellers embarking on a road to self-discovery.     

Episode 1 : Tara picks up Rohan and Bharati from the airport, before embarking on a ten-hour ferry "Dering" to the Little Andamans. As they set sail, they witness a school of dolphins giving them company, before they reach Little Andamans. Here they discover Andamans' famed forests with trees the size of "three-storied buildings," and some of the most surreal sights and sounds, such as "The Big Waterfall."

description:
Barack Obama encourages Vietnamese rapper Suboi to do an impromptu performance at a town hall meeting in Ho Chi Minh on Wednesday. After Obama starts her off by beatboxing, Suboi performs an a cappella verse. The two then went on to discuss gender stereotypes in music.

title: Way Back Home | A Himalayan Travelogue : Episode 7
description:
(The Vibe Originals - Tune into Way Back Home | A Himalayan Travelogue on The Vibe : https://goo.gl/NZXXeG)

The Vibe presents Way Back Home | A Himalayan Travelogue, a first-of-its-kind travelogue on India as it trails young, authentic, passionate travellers embarking on a road to self-discovery.

In Season 1, protagonist Rohan Thakur, aka Ronnie, a young Himachali lad embarks on an introspective journey of self-discovery across the seven valleys of the Lower Himalayan ranges. 
With a mission to travel, not tour, Ronnie takes the audience along with him on an unforgettable journey in true, authentic style.

Covering an entire diaspora of activities steeped in travel, adventure, music, lifestyle, people and fun, the Way Back Home series is crafted in rich, unscripted cinematic style with soulfully tailor-made background scores that capture the essence of life and diversity of Indian terrains.

In Episode 7, The panoramic views in whitewashed Spiti provide a feast for eyes.

Produced By: Shoelace Films

Filmed & Edited By: Rohan Thakur & Bharati Bahrani

description:
Barack Obama encourages Vietnamese rapper Suboi to do an impromptu performance at a town hall meeting in Ho Chi Minh on Wednesday. After Obama starts her off by beatboxing, Suboi performs an a cappella verse. The two then went on to discuss gender stereotypes in music.

title: Way Back Home | A Himalayan Travelogue : Episode 7
description:
(The Vibe Originals - Tune into Way Back Home | A Himalayan Travelogue on The Vibe : https://goo.gl/NZXXeG)

The Vibe presents Way Back Home | A Himalayan Travelogue, a first-of-its-kind travelogue on India as it trails young, authentic, passionate travellers embarking on a road to self-discovery.

In Season 1, protagonist Rohan Thakur, aka Ronnie, a young Himachali lad embarks on an introspective journey of self-discovery across the seven valleys of the Lower Himalayan ranges. 
With a mission to travel, not tour, Ronnie takes the audience along with him on an unforgettable journey in true, authentic style.

Covering an entire diaspora of activities steeped in travel, adventure, music, lifestyle, people and fun, the Way Back Home series is crafted in rich, unscripted cinematic style with soulfully tailor-made background scores that capture the essence of life and diversity of Indian terrains.

In Episode 7, The panoramic views in whitewashed Spiti provide a feast for eyes.

Produced By: Shoelace Films

Filmed & Edited By: Rohan Thakur & Bharati Bahrani

description:
Enjoy the sun, clear blue sea, white beach and beautiful green palm trees and take a tropical cocktail while watching and listening to the ocean waves and tropical birds chirping in the background. This beautiful peaceful white beach is recorded at Sunrise Beach, Koh Lipe in Thailand, and this soundscape video can give you a real holiday feeling without having to travel to your dream destination. So watch paradise on your screen every day!! This is real relaxation i hope you enjoy it!

‚óº All my soundscape videos are made in high quality with editing programs such as Vegas Pro, Photoshop and Audacity, and take many hours / days of editing and mixing to create. The equipment I use to record the audio are the Zoom H5 or H6 recorder + Audio-Technica BP4025 microphone, and for the videos I use the GoPro Hero6. Some video and audio files are made in collaboration with other video / audio creators with all the licenses & commercial use rights that are necessary. I mixed these video or audio files with the creation of myself. Sometimes I use a photo and make a moving video of it.

title: Northern Thailand Travel Ideas | Things to Do in Bangkok & Chiang Mai
tags: Things to do in Northern Thailand|Northern Thailand travel guide|Chiang Ma|Bangkok|Chang Rai
description:
Welcome to The Big Bus tour and travel guide's YouTube channel. Looking for ideas for things to do in Chiang Mai and Northern Thailand? In this episode of the Tour the World travel TV series we join On The Go Tours on tour through fabulous northern Thailand. 

The tour takes in bustling Bangkok and the key northern centres of Chiang Mai and Chiang Rai. We visit the Bridge over the River Kwai to learn more about this sad chapter in history, lend a hand at the Thai Elephant Conservation Centre and try a few interesting local delicacies!

Chapters

0:00 Introduction 
1:44 Map
6:33 Cultural attractions 
12:32 Historical attractions
16:10 Dining experiences
18:12 Shopping experiences
19:04 Ways to relax

To find more things to see and do in Bangkok, please visit: https://thebigbus.com.au/bangkok-travel-guide/.

To find more things to see and do in Chang Mai, head to: https://thebigbus.com.au/ten-top-things-to-do-in-chiang-mai/.

To book tours and experiences in northern Thailand, visit: https://www.partner.viator.com/en/21827/Northern-Thailand/d22518-ttd.

To browse all our Thailand travel guides and destination blogs, visit: https://thebigbus.com.au/tag/thailand/.

title: British Replaces Missing Teeth with Implants "There was absolutely no pain!" Part 1 #BIDC 85

description:
Mark Winnard from United Kingdom came to BIDC Dental Hospital in Thailand for 5 dental implants in replacing 8 missing teeth. The dental treatment as well as deep cleaning was completed in 2 trips with review of no pain from during the procedure.

‚ÄúHi my name is Mark I'm from the United Kingdom I came to Thailand the twelve the end of 2014 to seek Dental Treatment because a lot of my teeth where in a very false state of decay so after many hours of research online I decided to come to Bangkok International Dental Center for a consultation in December of last year and so after having get Deep Clean under the assessment of all my teeth We decided together the best cost of action would be to have five Implants which effectively replace eight teeth so I have my Implants fitted in December and I return six months later to have the abutments and Crowns fitted all I can say extremely happy with the quality of treatment through out the procedure there was no pain when the Implants were being loaded and was absolutely no pain when the Crowns being fitted which was last week everything about my new teeth functionality is absolutely perfect so and the price which a fraction of what I would expect to pay in the UK basically so I would not hesitate to recommend Bangkok International Dental Center to anybody in the World the serious about quality Dental Treatment Thank You Very Much‚Äù

title: Mekong River Cruise: the Journey of a Lifetime
tags: aqua expeditions|aqua mekong|vietnam cruises|cambodia cruises|southeast asia|vietnam adventure travel|cambodia adventure travel|Mekong (River)|Cruise Ship (Transit Vehicle Type)|Vietnam (Country)|Mekong River Cruise
description:
Aqua Expedition | Are you ready to embark on the journey of a lifetime? 
Join our Luxury cruise through the Mekong River. Watch our video and find out why YOU want to be aboard!

***************************************

Our Cruises:

Amazon River Cruise: The Journey of a Lifetime
‚ñ∫ https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NQF-AskOvhk

***************************************

Mekong River Cruise:

Culture and civilisations have flourished around great rivers throughout history, and the Mekong is no exception. The opportunity to discover rich heritage and traditions enriched by 2,000 years of human history is what makes the Mekong river cruise one of Asia‚Äôs most epic and worthwhile journeys on water.

A traveler cruising the Mekong is in close pursuit of a glorious past, retracing significant human accomplishments and cultural highs. From the flourishing of the Khmer empire from the 9th to 15th century to the prominence of Theravada Buddhism in present-day Cambodia and Vietnam, this is one of the few cultural destinations on Earth that‚Äôs best explored on a river voyage.

At the same time, the lower Mekong basin is also a cradle for nature. It‚Äôs home to a wealth of fish that provides sustenance for the people and a myriad species of large waterbirds. In the verdant rice fields dotted with pockets of lush greenery, more bird and domestic wildlife species can be spotted along with the ubiquitous Brahman oxen that diligently work the fields.

Aqua Expeditions‚Äô luxury river cruise ship, Aqua Mekong, charts a path through the picturesque lower Mekong basin with expert guides and 5-star dining on board. Navigating the Mekong river aboard our best-in-class vessel and following in the footsteps of royalty who have sailed before, this is the most enjoyable and rewarding way to experience the region.

Take this journey of a lifetime aboard the award-winning Aqua Mekong river cruise ship for a truly immersive, meaningful and personalized luxury experience in this culture-rich landscape. Itineraries depart from Ho Chi Minh City, Phnom Penh, and Siem Reap. Aqua Expeditions is the only Mekong cruise that provides complimentary flight extensions to Siem Reap during the low water season.

Begin your journey with us!
https://www.aquaexpeditions.com/mekong-river-cruise/

title: Vietnam Travel Ideas | Things to Do in Hanoi, Hoi An & HCMC
tags: Things to see and do in Vietnam|Vietnam|Hanoi|Hue|Hoi An|Ho Chi Minh City|Vietnam travel guide
description:
Welcome to The Big Bus tour and travel guide's YouTube channel. Looking for ideas for things to do in Hanoi, Ho Chi Minh City, Hoi An and Hue? In this episode of the Tour the World travel TV series, we join Wendy Wu Tours on an incredible journey through Vietnam. This is the perfect introduction to Vietnam as a travel destination, with visits to all the key cultural centres. 

Starting in bustling Saigon, we visit the infamous Cu Chi tunnels, before heading north to gorgeous Hoi An, Hue and former French-provincial capital Hanoi. 

Finally we enjoy an amazing cruise on the serene waters of Halong Bay. 

Chapters

0:00 Introduction 
1:35 Map
2:39 Tour guide interview
6:12 Cultural attractions 
12:56 Historical attractions
16:54 Dining experiences
18:10 Shopping experiences
20:03 Ways to relax

description:
Just a short Video, as you know I love a Daily coffee or two and we have been learning fast where to get the best Coffee at a fair price in Bangkok, Thailand....

GET $44 Aussie Dollars OFF AIRBNB
‚Ü™Ô∏é  https://abnb.me/e/YVGVBgDDOS

SUBSCRIBE so you never miss a new video: http://bit.ly/SKSubscibe 

Currently I haven't found coffee that matches my expectation but I have found that reasonable coffee doesn't have to cost much. With Starbucks selling coffee at prices that rival wealthier countries don't be surprised that locals don't have to spend those crazy prices for a decent Coffee

I will Add that I have found street vendors a little hit and miss. SUGAR!! a word of warning, if you don't have sugar in your coffee, you are going to find the default SUPER Sweet coffee almost un drinkable, so get and learn how to ask for no sugar ASAP ;o)
