title: Ko Phi Phi & Railey, Thailand in 4K (Ultra HD)
tags: Koh Phi Phi|Ko Phi Phi|Phi Phi Leh|Phi Phi Don|Phra Nang|Railey beach|Railey West|Railey East|Rai Leh|karst|limestone|cliff|island|beach|Thailand|UHD|AX100|HD|4K|ultra high definition|Ultra HD|world travel|milosh9k|Amazing Places on Our Planet|Phi Phi Islands (Island Group)|4K Resolution|Tourism (Interest)|tour|documentary|top 10 beaches|4K Ultra HD|top 10 Thailand
description:
The beaches of Ko Phi Phi Islands and the Railey peninsula are framed by stunning limestone cliffs. They are regularly listed between the top beaches in Thailand.

Phi Phi Leh island is famous as location of the movie "The Beach" (Leonardo DiCaprio). Phra Nang and Railey West are located on the Railey peninsula and are accessible only by boat.

Recorded February 2015 in 4K (Ultra HD) with Sony AX100. Edited with Adobe Premiere Pro CC.

title: Throw Net Fishing Vietnam
tags: Fisherman|Hoi An|Vietnam|Net|Fish|Throw Net|Cast Net|Magnet Fishing|Throw Net fishing
description:
Throw Net fishing Vietnam 
Cast Net Fishing Hoi An, Vietnam

A fisherman throws his cast net into the Thu Bon River, 

This use to be the way of fishing yet the large fishing boats have sucked all the fish out of the rivers and oceans and the locals now use the cast net to show how it was done to maintain fish supply. 

Staple diet of these locals. We tourist now come on a tours to learn from the fisherman how to throw cast net.

title: Mandalay, Myanmar in 4K (Ultra HD)
tags: Mandalay|Kuthodaw Pagoda|Mandalay Hill|Sandamuni Pagoda|Royal Palace|Mahamuni Temple|Mingun|Mingun pagoda|Mingun Paya|Hsinbyume Pagoda|Settawya Pagoda|Bodawpaya|Sagaing Hill|Inwa|Amarapura|U Bein Bridge|Myanmar|Burma|temple|pagoda|shrine|stupa|buddhist|UHD|AX100|HD|4K|ultra high definition|Ultra HD|milosh9k|Amazing Places on Our Planet|4K Resolution|tour|Tourism (Interest)|documentary|travel|Top 10 Myanmar|4K Ultra HD
description:
Mandalay was the last Royal Capital of Myanmar/Burma, founded in mid 19 century. Close to Mandalay are the remains of other royal capitals, spanning the history from early 14th century: Sagaing, Inwa (1364), Amarapura (1783). The most amazing site in the area is the great pagoda in Mingun, unfinished and later damaged by earthquake (1839).

In the video - Mandalay: Kuthodaw Pagoda, Mandalay Hill, Sandamuni Pagoda, Royal Palace, Mahamuni Temple. Mingun: Mingun Pagoda, Hsinbyume Pagoda, Settawya Pagoda. Sagaing Hill, U Bein Bridge in Amarapura.

Recorded February 2015 in 4K (Ultra HD) with Sony AX100.

title: Ajahn Sumedho : ¬´ Reflections on Dhamma #1 ¬ª
tags: Dhamma Talk|Public Dhamma Talk|Ajahn Sumedho|Sumedho Bhikkhu|Luang Por Sumedho|Theravada|Theravada Forest tradition|Ajahn Chah tradition|BIA|Buddhadasa Indapanno Archives|Suan Mokkh Bangkok|Sumedho|Rajasumedhajahn|dhamma|dharma|Thai forest tradition|Wat Pah Nanachat|Forest Sangha|Ajahn Chah|Buddhism|Thailand|Bangkok|Buddhadasa Bhikkhu
description:
Dhamma talk with Q&A session offered by Venerable Ajahn Sumedho (Phra Raja Sumedhajahn), who co-founded Wat Pah Nanachat in north-east Thailand and established Wat Amaravati in England, two monasteries in the Thai forest tradition of Ajahn Chah
http://www.watpahnanachat.org & http://www.amaravati.org

'Reflections on Dhamma #1'
22nd March , 2015 (13.00 - 14.30)
Meditation Hall
BuddhadƒÅsa Indapa√±√±o Archives, Bangkok

[Q&A session starts at 53:42]

For other teachings by Ven. Ajahn Sumedho, please visit:
https://www.amaravati.org/speakers/ajahn-sumedho/
https://forestsangha.org/teachings/books/authors/ajahn-sumedho?language=English 
http://www.bia.or.th/en/index.php/teachings-at-the-centre/forest-sangha/ven-ajahn-sumedho-audios

About Luang Por Sumedho:
After ordaining at the age of 30, Ajahn Sumedho was to be the first western disciple of Luang Por Chah in Wat Nong Pah Pong, Ubon, in North Eastern Thailand. In 1975 Luang Por Chah sent him to a nearby village, Bahn Bung Wai, to establish Wat Pah Nanachat, a monastery that english speaking people could go to in order to study Buddhism and ordain. Two years later, upon the invitation of George Sharp and the English Sangha Trust, Luang Por Chah asked Ajahn Sumedho to go to London. A small but growing community was to spend two years in the Hampstead VihƒÅra, before moving to West Sussex, to found Chithurst Monastery. Under Ajahn Sumedho's guidance, the community grew steadily. Ajahn Sumedho helped found a number of branch monasteries over the years, both in England and abroad, in countries such as Italy, Switzerland, New-Zealand, U.S.A, Canada,... A few years after living in Chithurst Monastery, he himself moved to establish Amaravati Buddhist Monastery, in Hertfordshire. He lived altogether 34 years in England, travelling regularly back to Thailand to keep in touch with the Sangha there, and all over the world, spreading the Buddha's Teaching.

Having retired from his position as the abbot of Amaravati Buddhist Monastery, Luang Por Sumedho has been living for the last four years in Wat Pah Ratanawan, in Central Thailand. He is now 80 years old, and still makes himself available according to his ability for teaching and encouraging people's interest in the Dhamma.

title: Our Favorite Pho in Ho Chi Minh City!
channel_title: Back of the Bike Tours - Ho Chi Minh Food and City Tours
tags: Pho|Vietnamese Pho|Vietnamese food|best vietnamese food|Vietnam (Country)|Saigon|streetfood tour|Vietnamese Food (Cuisine)|visit vietnam|try Vietnamese food|Pho in Saigon|Best pho in Vietnam|the best pho in the world|where is the best pho|vietnamese street food
description:
Chad and Fred catch up over a bowl of ph·ªü at Pho Le, 413 Nguyen Trai street in Saigon Vietnam learn more about Pho in Ho Chi Minh City here https://backofthebiketours.com/the-best-pho-in-the-world-saigons-pho-le/

Pho, the ambassador of Vietnamese street food across the entire globe. This one dish has helped spark an entire foodie movement of Vietnamese Street Food fans who come to Vietnam searching for a delicious bowl of Beef Noodle soup. 

If you want to learn even more about Ho Chi Minh City Street Food be sure to check out our playlist here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLo3gAYGXuVKaulZJmO6kbgI1mFhOM2v_8

What is Pho?

Simply put, a beef broth soup with flat rice noodles, braised beef, and fresh herbs. It's a Vietnamese street food that can be found up and down the entire country of Vietnam and can differ greatly in style depending on where you are eating in Vietnam or even across the globe. The dish can be rather inexpensive around 30,000 VND or extremely pricey like 18 AUD in places like Sydney or some upscale restaurants in Vietnam.

Saigon Pho vs. Hanoi Pho

Whats the difference? The amount of ingredients would be the simplest answer. For many many years Northern Vietnam, which is where Pho orginated, was one of the poorest areas in Vietnam. The classic bowl of Pho here, would have been very simple with the least amount of ingredients found inside the broth and the garnish inside of the soup. In southern vietnam, the addition of Thai Basil, Sawtooth Coriander, Mint, and Bean Sprouts is a common site at most any Pho restaurant but that is not the case in Northern Vietnam. The garnish would have been added into the broth and would simply be green onion and sliced white onion. This is a simplified version, there are a few other differences but I'll leave that to a much longer blog post to dive into the history, origin, and differences of Pho across Vietnam. 

How is Pho prounonced?

If you say the phrase, "What the F*", the beginning of the bad word would be the correct pronunciation. You don't want to say it like the word, Foe. Remember, Pho is your friend, not your foe!

What does Pho mean in Vietnamese?

Pho will actually refer to the rice noodle used inside of the beef noodle soup. Its a flat, long rice noodle that will be fresh and not dried. In Vietnamese Cuisine, if you use that noodle for a different dish, you would then use the word "pho" to describe it and the Vietnamese would understand that you are talking about the noodle and not the beef soup.

What ingredients can you find inside of Pho Broth?

The classic style of cooking Pho broth is time consuming. It takes up to 8 hours to boil beef bones to get the flavored broth you will need for a great bowl of Pho. Burnt onion and ginger is used inside of the broth, along with other various spices that will depend on each cooks own recipe. If you want to experiment you can start with Cinnamon sticks, Black cardamom, fennel seeds, cloves, and coriander seeds. Don't get caught up in being such a purist that it stops you from making your own pho, there are many recipes and videos out there showing how to make a much quicker pho that most Vietnamese households use. Most families are so busy that they aren't going to spend 12 hours to make a bowl of Pho for family dinner. Don't be worried and just jump in and have fun!

title: Planespotting at Koh Samui Airport - Bangkok Airways pushback and takeoff - Koh Samui Plane Spotting
tags: Koh Samui Airport|Samui Airport|Bangkok Airways|Airbus A320|pushback|Taxiing|plane spotting at|plane spotting at Koh Samui|Plane spotting at Samui|Pagoda Khao Hua Jook|aircraft|Koh Samui Airport Plane Spotting|Koh Samui Airport Planespotting|Planespotting at Koh Samui Airport|Plane Spotting at Koh Samui Airport|Samui Airport Plane Spotting|Bangkok Airways Takeoff|Koh Samui Travel Videos|Koh Samui Videos|Bangkok Airways Videos
description:
We are standing at Pagoda Khao Hua Jook Temple (hence the bells that are sometimes heard in the background) on Koh Samui Island in Thailand, looking down and plane spotting at Koh Samui Airport (USM). Samui Airport is a very small airport with a limited amount of daily flights going in and out of Koh Samui. The majority of flights on and off the island are operated by Bangkok Airways who were also the builders of the airport. 

Construction of Koh Samui Airport started in 1982 and the airport was officially opened in April 1989. Other airlines flying in and out of this airport include Thai Airways, Silk Air and Firefly Airlines. Koh Samui Airport is located approximately 2 kilometers North of Chaweng Beach (close to Lamai Beach too), one of the main tourist hubs on this Thai island located in the Gulf of Thailand.

The Bangkok Airways Airbus A319¬¥s featured in this footage include an  Airbus A319-131 with registration HS-PPF (Pushback) and an Airbus A319-132 with registration HS-PPA called Si Satchanalai (Takeoff). The destination of these two Airbus aircraft is unknown but they were more than likely flying to Bangkok, Singapore, Hong Kong or Kuala Lumpur. HS-PPF was delivered to Bangkok Airways in May 2013 and has previously also been operated by BBAM (with aircraft registration EI-EXZ) and Kingfisher Airlines (with aircraft registration VT-KFI). HS-PPF her her first flight in December 2005. HS-PPA (Si Satchanalai) was delivered to Bangkok Air in May 2009. This aircraft had her first flight in May 2009 and has therefore only been operated by Bangkok Air.

Wiki writes about Bangkok Airways, "Bangkok Airways Public Company Limited is a regional airline based in Vibhavadi Rangsit Road, Chatuchak District, Bangkok, Thailand. It operates scheduled services to destinations in Thailand, Cambodia, China, Hong Kong, Laos, Maldives, Burma, India and Singapore. Its main base is Suvarnabhumi Airport, Bangkok. Bangkok Airways is currently an official sponsor of Bangkok Glass FC, Chiang Mai FC, Trat FC, Lampang FC, Sukhothai FC and Bangkok Christian College FC. Airline ranking company Skytrax has consistently ranked Bangkok Airlines very highly, currently giving them a four-star rating...".

Wiki writes about Koh Samui Airport, "Samui International Airport, also known as Ko Samui Airport or Koh Samui Airport, is a privately owned airport on the island of Ko Samui (Koh Samui) in Thailand...The airport has two terminals (Domestic & International). The International terminal is located about 50 metres north of the domestic. Samui Airport is located near the Big Buddha Pier where ferries depart to Ko Pha Ngan. High speed ferries to Koh Tao and Chumphon depart from the Maenam Beach Pier, approximately 6 km north-west of the airport..."

Airbus writes about the Airbus A319, "As a shortened-fuselage version of Airbus‚Äô A320 cornerstone single-aisle jetliner, the A319 continues to prove its versatility ‚Äì enabling carriers around the world to benefit from the aircraft‚Äôs range options and seat layout flexibility...In addition to the standard 124-seat configuration with a range of up to 3,740 nautical miles, Airbus offers an option with a seating capacity of up to 156 passengers ‚Äì a version that is being ordered by an increasing number of low-cost airlines..."

This aviation footage from Koh Samui Airport (USM) is filmed on the island of Koh Samui located in the Gulf of Thailand Sea in Thailand. We are filming Koh Samui Airport from above at a beautiful monks temple called Pagoda Khao Hua Jook. This is one of Koh Samui¬¥s must see attractions as it is also a view point offering fantastic views to the North, South, East and West of Koh Samui Airport. If you enjoy a birds Eye View of airports then this tropical airport is a plane spotters dream! Only drawback is the limited number of flights and the limited number of airlines! This footage is filmed with a Panasonic HC-V520.

title: Shwedagon Pagoda, Myanmar in 4K (Ultra HD)
tags: Shwedagon Pagoda|Yangon|Rangoon|Myanmar|Burma|sunrise|sunset|temple|pagoda|buddhist|UHD|AX100|HD|4K|ultra high definition|Ultra HD|world travel|milosh9k|Amazing Places on Our Planet|4K Resolution|tour|Tourism (Interest)|Buddhism (Religion)|documentary|Top 10 Myanmar|4K Ultra HD|·Äõ·ÄΩ·Äæ·Ä±·Äê·Ä≠·ÄÇ·ÄØ·Ä∂·ÄÖ·Ä±·Äê·ÄÆ·Äê·Ä±·Ä¨·Ä∫|·Äô·Äº·Äî·Ä∫·Äô·Ä¨
description:
The Shwedagon Pagoda is the most impressive and sacred Buddhist site in Myanmar. The pagoda is claimed to be 2,600 years old, but according to the historians and archaeologists it was built between 6th and 10th centuries. It has been damaged by earthquakes on several occasions and later rebuilt and raised higher, to its current height of 99 meters/325 ft.
In the video: Early morning/Sunrise and late afternoon/Sunset views of the pagoda and the surrounding temples, stupas and shrines.

Recorded February 2015 in 4K (Ultra HD) with Sony AX100.

The sacred Popa Taung Kalat monastery sits incredibly atop a huge rocky outcrop. 777 steps lead to the top, offering stunning views of the surrounding plains and Mount Popa. title: Patara Elephant Farm in Chiang Mai, Thailand (See Description)
tags: Tourist Destination|I am Aileen|Elephants|Travel Blog|Travel Blogger|Vlog|Aileen|Asia|Asian|Adalid|asian|elephant|patara farm|patara elephant farm|elephant farm|thailand|chiang mai|iamaileen|aileen adalid|aileen vlog|aileen blog|patara|travel vlogger|travel blog|patara chiang mai|elephant sanctuary|southeast asia|trunk|bathing|feeding|elephants|baby elephants|tour|things to do in chiang mai|thai|animals
description:
***UPDATE as of 2/5/2016: I don‚Äôt fully support Patara Elephant Farm anymore after the reality of their practices were fully disclosed to me. For sure, I love that they help these animals breed and they wholly care for their health. Their team really takes care of them on that aspect; but at the very core‚Ä¶ the elephants are still trained and tamed to interact with people ‚Äî and this just makes me sad. It makes me even more sad and ethically-conflicted that I have unknowingly supported this activity.

Now why do I say this? For instance, I just found out that the reason why all their attendants have shoulder bags with them is because they are hiding their bull hooks in it ‚Äî just in case the elephants do something that they don‚Äôt instruct them to do. I was even properly educated of the fact that if they are still able to interact with tourists and do these rides (even though deemed as safer), then it means that they are still ‚Äúbroken‚Äù and tamed. (You will see in the video as well how they can still perform tricks: raising their trunks, splashing water on us, etc.) For sure some have been rescued from circus so they still know these tricks; but don‚Äôt you think it‚Äôs a bit cruel to let them continue such a practice? Elephants are not meant to be pets. They are meant for the wild.

Additionally, since these animals have been ‚Äúbroken‚Äù, there is still a chance that they can show their cruelty after all the harsh treatment they have received ‚Äî so your safety isn‚Äôt exactly guaranteed in Patara (this is why you‚Äôll be signing documents before the experience). We must remember that elephants belong to the wild ‚Äî they‚Äôre not meant to mingle with us humans. With this in mind, if you want a more responsible activity with elephants in Thailand, please go to Elephant Nature Park instead which is also located in Chiang Mai.

Meanwhile, I have decided to leave this video and keep the article on my website "AS IS" and not edit anything to show you how the ‚Äòhype‚Äô of the experience has mislead me; but that I hope with this warning at the start, it will highlight to you the things that we did that then proves this claim.

But of course, overall: I leave it up to you to decide whether you will visit Patara or not. But it is my wish that this note will urge you to think harder and choose a better activity that does not contribute to the harm of these gentle giants. Better yet, I hope Patara changes its program and function more like that of a nature reserve like Elephant Nature Park.

title: üá≤üá≤ Myanmar (Burma): a travel documentary
tags: Travel Documentary (TV Genre)|Travel (TV Genre)|Myanmar (Country)|Yangon (City/Town/Village)|Bagan (City/Town/Village)|Inle Lake (Lake)|Pindaya Caves (Place Of Worship)|Mrauk U (City/Town/Village)|Rakhine State (Administrative Division)|Adventure (TV Genre)|Guglielmo Biason|Valentina Vitali|On the Road
description:
#Myanmar #Travel #Documentary

Overall, Burma has been probably one if not the most breathtaking country we ever travelled. Despite officially being one of the poorest place in the world, we found very industrious and friendly people. 

Yangon: the capital is not too bad to spend 2 days (no more). The Shwedagon Paya at sunset is an inspirational place while walking around in the city center will reveal magnificent and huge colonial buildings, often abandoned. One memorable experience was to take the train to Bagan. What was supposed to be a 14h journey over 600km ... turned to be a 20h journey across magnificent landscape. The very slow speed of the train and the big open windows gave the feeling to be cycling in the Burmese country side. 

Once in Bagan, the magnificence of this country came to the peak. The 2,000 temples immersed in a green landscape are amazing. Exploring them is an experience that is at the same time cultural (for the history), mystical (they are still places of worship) and athletical (you can climb on top of the roof on most of them). Buddhist temples are not only places to prey, but their courts are places to meet and spend time with the family. In Bagan, thanks to the help of a group of local women, me also manage to get a ride and navigate, for a little while, the Irrawady river, the main river of Myanmar.

The Inle Lake was our next stop after Bagan. While it‚Äôs utterly beautiful, it‚Äôs probably the most touristic place in Myanmar and that spoils a bit the atmosphere. Anyway, watching the local fishermen fishing at sunset is something breathtaking. Inle Lake is not the only attraction here. After we were done with the lake, we move exploring the hills of the surrounding area, where agriculture is the main occupation for the population. We even discovered a wine estate producing very good white and red wines.

The last part of our trip was Mrauk-U, a remote rural village at the border with Bangladesh. This was the capital of the Rakhine State and during the 1500 ‚Äì 1600 AD, was one of the most important cities in Asia. We looked at a painting done in the 1600 and shows a big city with long walls, a quarter for European merchants and a number of vessels and ships trading in the port. Now, the remaining temples and walls are to be found in the wheat fields.

description:
Yangon Circular Railway
is the local commuter rail network that serves the Yangon metropolitan area. Operated by Myanmar Railways, the 45,9 km (28.5 mi) 39-Station-loop-System connects satellite towns and suburban areas to the city. The loop, which takes about three hours to complete, is a way to see a cross section of life in Yangon. Foreigners pay about 1000 Kyat in a little ticket office on platform seven in Central Railway Station regardless of the length oft the journey.

title: Koh Lanta  - Thailand January - February 2014
tags: koh lanta thailand|koh lanta|ko lanta thailand|lanta|February|January|thailand|Action|gorgeous beaches|hot baths|sandy beach|colorful fish|good drinks|Thais|Phuket|underwater camera|Canon EOS 7D|GoPro|monkeys|poor monkey|vacation|holiday|travel|speedboat|island tour|fair weather|Krabi province of Southern Thailand|GoPro Hero4 Black|Fy G4 Gimbal|Hero 4 Black|Platanias - Agii Apostoli|Thai massage|thai food|sao miguel azores|azores
description:
Koh Lanta is located in Phang Nga Bay mouth a bit south of Krabi and Phi Phi Islands of Southern Thailand with its beautiful places for cozy and romantic excursions and wonderful evenings. Along the beaches there are a large number of cozy restaurants that light up your life with candlelight. Lots of bars on the beaches, where you can have a drink, sit barefoot on the scissors chairs and listen to music to the surging sea. Try the miraculous Thai massage on the beach. What an experience to sit atop an elephant through the jungle of wild monkeys, or take a ride on the Jeep Safari in the jungle. Klong Dao is the island's most densely populated and lively beach. Long Beach (Klong Phra-Ae) is the island's most beautiful beach. Klong Khong Beach that is genuinely Thai with light sand. Klong Nin is a peaceful place with a wide selection of beach restaurants, shops and mini-markets. Visit the famous Emerald Cave on Koh Mook for wonderful snorkeling. 
My recommendations. Travel to Koh Lanta in Thailand if you are longing for lovely bathing, sun and well-being.

title: American Nurse "Matches standards in America" on Teeth Fillings #BIDC 81
tags: Dental Restoration (Medical Treatment)|Teeth|Bangkok (City/Town/Village)|Nursing (Field Of Study)|United States Of America|dental review
description:
Patient from USA provides her review on having teeth filling  at BIDC Thailand Dental Clinic. 

‚ÄúI'm an expat here living in Bangkok Thailand. 

I came to this dental clinic because one of my good friends recommended it to me.I told her that I wanted to go to the absolute best. She said that this place was perfect for me that I would find everything that I wanted, so I came here and that was exactly what I found!

I was so happy with the care here. I think that it is really modern. Everything that they have here is advanced enough to standards. The staff was so polite, and so friendly.

They explained in detail everything they needed to have done. All the costs, they helped me to fill out the forms, and they spoke english which is really nice.

My dentist was awesome! It was the best dental work that I had done. It was amazing! She explained my x-rays to me. She sat down and talked to me about the treatment, the post care and work required. She asked if I was ok repeated over the procedure. 

I have already recommended BIDC to everybody that I know. I love it here!

I work at a dental clinic in America and this definately matches the standards that they have with the healthcare standards, the safety, the cleanliness and sterilization. Everything is definately up to code.

I would come here again and tell this to everyone. Its prefect and a really good experience for me!‚Äù

title: Vipassana Meditation
tags: Meditation (Quotation Subject)|VipassanƒÅ (Religious Practice)|Religion (TV Genre)|New-age Music (Musical Genre)|Vipassana Meditation
description:
10 Days Meditation courses experience, at Thailand Dhamma Porano Nakhon Si Thammaraj. From 17 Sep to 28 Sep 2014. Language Nepali & English. 

Vipassana, which means to see things as they really are, is one of India's most ancient techniques of meditation. It was taught in India more than 2500 years ago as a universal remedy for universal ills, i.e., an Art of Living. For those who are not familiar with Vipassana Meditation, an Introduction to Vipassana by Mr. Goenka & related videos and Questions & Answers about Vipassana are available.

The technique of Vipassana Meditation is taught at ten-day residential courses during which participants learn the basics of the method, and practice sufficiently to experience its beneficial results. There are no charges for the courses - not even to cover the cost of food and accommodation. All expenses are met by donations from people who, having completed a course and experienced the benefits of Vipassana, wish to give others the opportunity to also benefit.

title: Australian engineer on Thailand dentist "Top-notch dentistry, holistic approach & painless" #BIDC 75
description:
Patient from Australia provides a review on having dental crowns and dental implants done at Bangkok International Dental Center (BIDC).

"My entire dental experience at BIDC as been tremendous. The staff that greet you makes you feel welcomed, they are kind and caring. They tell you exactly what you are going to do, its costs, what the treatment entails and does a followup. 

They have a holistic approach to treatment. Its not just coming here for a crown or filling and they take it as part of you're well-being. I have been absolutely happy and top notch. The equipment is fantastic. The facility is wonderful. The staff shares information to me readily means a lot to me.

As an engineer, it is important that one person knows what the other person is doing. Each of my specialists here has been able to know exactly what the other has done in real time and it affects the way that the treatment has gone for me, The treatment has basically been painless which has been wonderful.

They realize that you are a person that feels pain and scared and they take you through that journey. I would not hesitate to recommend BIDC!"

title: Wolfie the Grunt takes 8mm movies of a Combat Assault in Vietnam
tags: 8 Mm Film (Film Format)|Movie Camera (Invention)|Vietnam War (Military Conflict)|US Army|Infantry|Combat|23rd Infantry|Americal|Soldiers|Easter|1971|War|PTSD|VA Mental Health|VA C&P|Chaplain Merle Brown|Death in Vietnam|Last Chaplain to be killed in combat in Vietnam|Veterans Administration C&P|Veteran suicides|35+ Vets a day commit suicide
description:
I bought a 8mm Yashica film movie camera during a stand-down when we got out of the bush and out of combat.  I took movies during the stand-down and then decided to hump the camera into the bush on our next mission.  I took movies during the  airmobile combat assault.  After blocking out Vietnam for 36 years I decided to use my footage to pay tribute to the 11 men that were ambushed and killed on Easter Sunday 4-11-1971.  

The following day after our air mobile assault was Easter Sunday and Chaplain Merle Brown came out to give us Easter Services and he brought some hot food.  He asked us if he could join us for lunch, which we gladly said YES.  I was blessed to sit next to him and we talked for about an hour.  Chaplain Brown was a great man and I felt I had met a New Best Friend.

His helicopter came to pick him up and take him to another company that was very close to us on the top of a hill.  We were able to see him land and and when his helicopter came back to pick him up all hell broke loose.  The enemy fired rockets hitting the helicopter and it exploded 5 times.  

As I watched the explosions and then found out Chaplain Brown and 10 other men died day, I was devastated and a huge trauma to lose my new best friend.  I had other traumas in Vietnam, I was an infantry grunt and was in the bush for 11 months.  I was awarded a Combat Infantry Badge and an Air Medal.  You have to be in combat for over 6 months to get a CIB and many air mobile combat assaults to get an Air Medal.  

I have been treated by VA Mental Health Care for PTSD for 8 years and take 4 meds a day.  VA Mental Health says I have extreme PTSD and they believe I qualify for 100% comp.  I was awarded 70% VA disability, I get 100% health care, but no dental

When I took the camera into the bush I had extra film, but I didn't bring any spare batteries so I was unable to film this event.  We did have 35mm cameras so pictures were taken. 

I never expected my Nam videos to be seen over 1,002,000+ times.  In this version I decided to add personal narration.  By the way I have supplied my raw footage to 5 Vietnam documentaries including History Channel, PBS and others.  History Channel got the actual 8mm film and then upgraded it to High Definition and that's what I used in this video.  

I get great health care from the VA Health Care department and my caregiver in the VA Mental Health department keeps me alive right now.  I see her more than once a month.  We hug when I leave!

description:
The enormous depth of things to do and see in and around Bangkok is just one of the many reasons Thailand is so popular as a tourist destination, Here is another very clear example of this fact. It is in fact uncertain when Sriratcha Tiger Zoo first opened, however it was in 1982 when it first started caring for tigers. The zoo started with just 2 couples, and currently there are 345 Bengal tigers housed here, with numbers increasingly on the rise...the largest captive Bengal tiger population in the world.

title: Plane Spotting at Koh Samui Airport - SilkAir Airbus A319 Takeoff
tags: Silkair|Samui Airport|Airbus A319|Koh Samui Airport|plane spotting|avgeek|Airbus|Singapore Airport|Aircraft Spotting|Pagoda Khao Hua Jook Temple|Bangkok Airways|Singapore Changi Airport|Koh Samui spotting|Spotting at Koh Samui|Plane spotting at|Big Buddha Pier|Airbus A320 Family|Airport|Aircraft|Koh Samui Airport Planespotting|Koh Samui Airport Plane Spotting|Plane Spotting at Koh Samui Airport|Planespotting at Koh Samui Airport|Where to go planespotting
description:
This is takeoff footage of a Silk Air Airbus A319 TakeOff at Koh Samui Airport in Thailand. The video includes two separate aircraft whose takeoffs have been edited to produce one takeoff video. These aircraft have registrations 9V-SBD and 9V-SBE. We are standing at Pagoda Khao Hua Jook Temple (hence the bells that are sometimes heard in the background) on Koh Samui, Thailand looking down and plane spotting at Koh Samui Airport (USM). 

Koh Samui is a very small airport with a limited amount of daily flights going in and out of Koh Samui. The majority of flights on and off the island are operated by Bangkok Airways who were also the builders of the airport. Construction of Koh Samui Airport started in 1982 and the airport was officially opened in April 1989. Koh Samui is located approximately 2 kilometers North of Chaweng Beach, one of the main tourist hubs on this Thai island located in the Gulf of Thailand.

The footage shown in this video is of two Silkair Airbus A319-132¬¥s taking off from Koh Samui Airport. Both of these passenger aircraft where heading for Singapore Changi Airport (SIN). The A319 with the registration 9V-SBD (taking off) was delivered to SilkAir in March 2002. Prior to that this Silk Air Airbus has not had any previous owners or operators. The aircraft als had its first flight in March 2002. The second A319 with registration 9V-SBE was delivered to Silk Air in October 2005, prior to that this SilkAir Airbus does not appear to have been owned or operated by any other airline. This aircraft had its first flight in September 2005.

Wiki writes about SilkAir, "SilkAir (Singapore) Private Limited (Tamil: ‡Æö‡Æø‡Æ≤‡Øç‡Æï‡Øç‡Æè‡Æ∞‡Øç)(Chinese: ÂãùÂÆâËà™Á©∫ Sh√®ng'ƒÅn H√°ngk≈çng) is an airline with its head office in Airline House in Singapore; previously it was on the fifth storey of the SIA Superhub in Singapore. It is a wholly owned subsidiary of Singapore Airlines and operates scheduled passenger services from Singapore to 44 cities in Southeast Asia, the Indian Subcontinent, China and Australia. As the regional wing of Singapore Airlines, it serves the short-haul destinations in the Singapore Airlines Group network..."

Wiki writes about Koh Samui Airport, "Samui International Airport, also known as Ko Samui Airport or Koh Samui Airport, is a privately owned airport on the island of Ko Samui (Koh Samui) in Thailand...The airport has two terminals (Domestic & International). The International terminal is located about 50 metres north of the domestic. Samui Airport is located near the Big Buddha Pier where ferries depart to Ko Pha Ngan. High speed ferries to Koh Tao and Chumphon depart from the Maenam Beach Pier, approximately 6 km north-west of the airport..."

Airbus writes about the Airbus A319, "As a shortened-fuselage version of Airbus‚Äô A320 cornerstone single-aisle jetliner, the A319 continues to prove its versatility ‚Äì enabling carriers around the world to benefit from the aircraft‚Äôs range options and seat layout flexibility...In addition to the standard 124-seat configuration with a range of up to 3,740 nautical miles, Airbus offers an option with a seating capacity of up to 156 passengers ‚Äì a version that is being ordered by an increasing number of low-cost airlines..."

This aviation footage from Koh Samui Airport (USM) is filmed on the island of Koh Samui located in the Gulf of Thailand Sea in Thailand. We are filming Koh Samui Airport from above at a beautiful monks temple called Pagoda Khao Hua Jook. This is one of Koh Samui¬¥s must see attractions as it is also a view point offering fantastic views to the North, South, East and West of Koh Samui Airport. If you enjoy a birds Eye View of airports then this tropical airport is a plane spotters dream! Only drawback is the limited number of flights and the limited number of airlines!

title: Baba (Peranakan) - The Lost Culture of Phuket Thailand
tags: Thailand|Phuket|Phuket Baba|Baba Life|Peranakan|Phuket Old Town|Museum|Malay Peninsula|Malacca|Singapore|Hokkien|Tradition|Opulent|Ritual|Weddings|Chin Pracha House|Phuket Baba Weddings|Capital TV Bangkok|Nok Air|History|Tourism|Destination Thailand|Phuket Thailand|Phuket Baba Peranakan|Baba Peranakan|Phuket history|Phuket culture|baba|wedding|thai food|thailand travel|chinese wedding|Chinese|Things to do in Phuket|Travel|Phuket VLOG|Chinese food
description:
Phuket Thailand owes a lot to its  its cultural heritage to its Thai-Chinese Baba Peranakan (predominantly Hokkien) ancestry way of life, the minor culture once present in the Malay Peninsula. Today, it‚Äôs estimated that at least 70% of Phuket‚Äôs population has Peranakan ancestral roots.

Several Baba traditions in Phuket have died. Its significance and identity has been dwindled through time. But with the effort of some Phuketians  and local tourism units, some of the traditions such as food, costumes, and ceremonies have been brought back to life.

title: Plane Spotting at Samui Airport - Unstable and Hardish Landing of Bangkok Airways Airbus A319
tags: Hard landing|Unstable landing|Bangkok Airways|Airbus A319|Airbus A320|Samui Airport|Koh Samui Airport|Ko Samui|HS-PGN|Luang Prabang|Landing|Taxiing|Airplane|Plane|Koh Samui|plane spotting in Thailand|Flights from Koh Samui|Flights to Koh Samui|Scary landing|landing at koh samui airport|aviation videos|avgeek|aircraft|airplane|Aviation|Koh Samui Airport Plane Spotting|Koh Samui Airport Planespotting|Plane Spotting at Koh Samui Airport|Plane Spotting Videos
description:
This is footage of an unstable hardish landing (in my opinion... judge for yourself) of an Airbus A319 landing at Koh Samui Airport. Watch how the wing (with the engine) dips steeply to the left as the aircraft bounces from the right side landing gear to the left side and back again. Also notice how the tail (backside of the aircraft) appears to skid!!

We are standing at Pagoda Khao Hua Jook Temple (hence the bells that are sometimes heard in the background) on Koh Samui, Thailand looking down and plane spotting at Koh Samui Airport (USM). Koh Samui is a very small airport with a limited amount of daily flights going in and out of Koh Samui. The majority of flights on and off the island are operated by Bangkok Airways who where also the builders of the airport. Construction of Koh Samui Airport started in 1982 and the airport was officially opened in April 1989. Koh Samui is located approximately 2 kilometers North of Chaweng Beach, one of the main tourist hubs on this Thai island located in the Gulf of Thailand.

The footage shown in this video is of a Bangkok Airways Airbus Airbus A319 arriving from Hong Kong Airport (HKG) at Koh Samui Airport (USM). This Airbus A319-132 has aircraft registration HS-PGN and the aircraft is named "Luang Prabang".

This Bangkok Air Boeing Airbus A319-132 aircraft with registration HS-PGN was delivered to Bangkok Airways in January 2009 and they appear to be the only operators of this passenger aircraft. This Airbus A319 had it¬¥s first flight in January 2009.

Wiki writes about Bangkok Airways, "Bangkok Airways Public Company Limited is a regional airline based in Vibhavadi Rangsit Road, Chatuchak District, Bangkok, Thailand. It operates scheduled services to destinations in Thailand, Cambodia, China, Hong Kong, Laos, Maldives, Burma, India and Singapore. Its main base is Suvarnabhumi Airport, Bangkok.Bangkok Airways is currently an official sponsor of Bangkok Glass FC, Chiang Mai FC, Trat FC, Lampang FC, Sukhothai FC and Bangkok Christian College FC. Airline ranking company Skytrax has consistently ranked Bangkok Airlines very highly, currently giving them a four-star rating..."

Wiki writes about Koh Samui Airport, "Samui International Airport, also known as Ko Samui Airport or Koh Samui Airport, is a privately owned airport on the island of Ko Samui (Koh Samui) in Thailand...The airport has two terminals (Domestic & International). The International terminal is located about 50 metres north of the domestic. Samui Airport is located near the Big Buddha Pier where ferries depart to Ko Pha Ngan. High speed ferries to Koh Tao and Chumphon depart from the Maenam Beach Pier, approximately 6 km north-west of the airport..."

Wiki writes about, Luang Prabang , "The Luang Prabang Range, named after Luang Prabang, is a mountain range straddling northwestern Laos and Northern Thailand. Most of the range is located in Sainyabuli Province (Laos), as well as Nan and Uttaradit Provinces (Thailand), with small parts in Phitsanulok and Loei Provinces. Several rivers such as the Nan, Pua and Wa river, have their source in this range.Phu Fa waterfall, the biggest and the tallest waterfall in Nan Province, is also located in these mountains..."

Airbus writes about the Airbus A319, "As a shortened-fuselage version of Airbus‚Äô A320 cornerstone single-aisle jetliner, the A319 continues to prove its versatility ‚Äì enabling carriers around the world to benefit from the aircraft‚Äôs range options and seat layout flexibility...In addition to the standard 124-seat configuration with a range of up to 3,740 nautical miles, Airbus offers an option with a seating capacity of up to 156 passengers ‚Äì a version that is being ordered by an increasing number of low-cost airlines..."

We are filming Koh Samui Airport from above at a beautiful monks temple called Pagoda Khao Hua Jook. This is one of Koh Samui¬¥s must see attractions as it is also a view point offering fantastic views to the North, South, East and West of Koh Samui Airport. title: Apocalypse Now movie soundtrack - Ride of the Valkyries - ATR 72-500 lands at Koh Samui Airport
tags: Theme song Apocalypse Now|Landing|ATR 72|Firefly|Koh Samui|Ride of the Valkyries|Ko Samui|Song|Aircraft|airport|airplane|Wagner|Apocalypse Now Soundtrack|Aviation music video|Richard Wagner|Walk√ºrenritt or Ritt der Walk√ºren|ATR|Apocalypse Now Movie Soundtrack|Samui Airport|Aviation videos|plane spotting|avgeek|Thailand|Movie soundtracks|Aviation|taxiing|9M-FYE|Khao Hua Jook|Fireflyz|Apocalypse Now: The Ride of the Valkyries
description:
The theme song from Apocalypse Now, Ride of the Valkyries, plays while a Fireflyz ATR-72-500 passenger aircraft slowly approaches, lands and taxis with multiple close-ups at Koh Samui Airport. This song taken from the Apocalypse Now movie soundtrack is written by Richard Wagner. In German the song is called "Walk√ºrenritt or Ritt der Walk√ºren.

We are standing at Pagoda Khao Hua Jook Temple (hence the bells that are sometimes heard in the background) on Koh Samui, Thailand looking down and plane spotting at Koh Samui Airport (USM). Koh Samui is a very small airport with a limited amount of daily flights going in and out of Koh Samui. The majority of flights on and off the island are operated by Bangkok Airways who where also the builders of the airport. Construction of Koh Samui Airport started in 1982 and the airport was officially opened in April 1989. Koh Samui is located approximately 2 kilometers North of Chaweng Beach, one of the main tourist hubs on this Thai island located in the Gulf of Thailand.

This landing footage of the Fireflyz ATR-72-500 landing is actually footage of three different aircraft of the same airline which have been filmed individually and have then been edited together to form one landing, taxiing and docking aviation music video! The registrations of the three aircraft are 9M-FYE (The main landing aircraft), 9M-FYC (The aircraft zoomed in on during landing) and 9M-FYF (The aircraft with close-up footage as the ATR-72 approaches her gate. All of these aircraft are ATR-72-500¬¥s and are operated bu the Malaysian Airline Fireflyz which is a part of Malaysian Airlines.
The footage shown in this video (with one of the theme songs from the Apocalypse Now movie soundtrack) is of a Fireflyz ATR-72-500 slowly landing at Koh Samui Airport (USM). This footage includes the landing and some very close-up footage as the aircraft taxis towards and arrives at it¬¥s docking area (departure gate), be sure to watch that!

This main Firefly aircraft landing with registration 9M-FYE is arriving from Subang (Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) (SZB). This aircraft was delivered to Firefly Airlines in December 2008 and that is the same month and year that the aircraft had its first flight.
The aircraft with registration number 9M-FYC (close up zoom while landing) was delivered to Firefly Airlines in September 2008 and also had its first flight in the same month and year.
The aircraft with registration number 9M-FYF (close-up taxiing footage) was delivered to Firefly Airlines in April 2009 and this aircraft had its first flight in March 2009.

Wiki writes about the movie Apocalypse Now, "Apocalypse Now is a 1979 American epic war film set during the Vietnam War, directed and produced by Francis Ford Coppola and starring Marlon Brando, Martin Sheen, and Robert Duvall. The film follows the central character, U.S. Army special operations officer Captain Benjamin L. Willard (Sheen), of MACV-SOG, on a mission to kill the renegade and presumed insane U.S. Army Special Forces Colonel Walter E. Kurtz (Brando)..."

Wiki writes about the Apocalypse Now movie theme song, "The Ride of the Valkyries (German: Walk√ºrenritt or Ritt der Walk√ºren) is the popular term for the beginning of Act III of Die Walk√ºre, the second of the four operas by Richard Wagner that constitute Der Ring des Nibelungen. The main theme of the Ride, the leitmotif labelled Walk√ºrenritt, was first written down by the composer on 23 July 1851. The preliminary draft for the Ride was composed in 1854 as part of the composition of the entire opera, which was fully orchestrated by the end of the first quarter of 1856..."
The music "The Ride of the Valkyries.

This aviation footage from Koh Samui Airport (USM) is filmed on the island of Koh Samui located in the Gulf of Thailand Sea in Thailand. We are filming Koh Samui Airport from above at a beautiful monks temple called Pagoda Khao Hua Jook. This is one of Koh Samui¬¥s must see attractions as it is also a view point offering fantastic views to the North, South, East and West of Koh Samui Airport. If you enjoy a birds Eye View of airports then this tropical airport is a plane spotters dream! Only drawback is the limited number of flights and the limited number of airlines!

tags: Takeoff|Take Off|Thai Airways|Koh Samui Airport|Boeing 737|Boeing|Plane spotter|Koh Samui Viewpoint|Airplane|Ko Samui|Pagoda Khao Hua Jook|Temple|Plane spotting in Thailand|Thailand airports|avgeek|Runway|Thailand|Thailand islands|HS-TDH|USM|Bangkok|BKK|aviation videos|plane videos|airplane|aircraft|Suvarnabhumi Airport|Flights to Koh samui|Flights from Koh Samui|Maenam Beach Pier|Ko Pha Ngan|Big Buddha Pier|Takeoffs|LOP BURI
description:
We are standing at Pagoda Khao Hua Jook Temple (hence the bells that are sometimes heard in the background) on Koh Samui, Thailand looking down and plane spotting at Koh Samui Airport (USM). Koh Samui is a very small airport with a limited amount of daily flights going in and out of Koh Samui. The majority of flights on and off the island are operated by Bangkok Airways who where also the builders of the airport. Construction of Koh Samui Airport started in 1982 and the airport was officially opened in April 1989. Koh Samui is located approximately 2 kilometers North of Chaweng Beach, one of the main tourist hubs on this Thai island located in the Gulf of Thailand.

The footage shown in this video is of a Thai Airways Boeing 737 takeoff from Koh Samui. This aircraft is bound for Bangkok, and is one of only a few (if not the only) daily Thai Airways flight on the island. This Boeing 737-4DR has aircraft registration HS-TDH and the aircraft is named "LOP BURI"..

This Thai Boeing 737-4D7 aircraft with registration HS-TDH was delivered to Thai Airways in December 1997 and they appear to be the only operators of this passenger aircraft. This Boeing 737 had it¬¥s first flight in November 1997.

Wiki writes about Thai Airways, "Thai Airways (a trading name of Thai Airways International Public Company Limited (THAI)) is the flag carrier airline of Thailand. Formed in 1988, the airline has its corporate headquarters in Vibhavadi Rangsit Road, Chatuchak District, Bangkok, and primarily operates out of Suvarnabhumi Airport. THAI is a founding member of the Star Alliance. The airline is the largest shareholder of the low-cost carrier Nok Air with a 49% stake, and it launched a regional carrier under the name Thai Smile in the middle of 2012 using new Airbus A320 aircraft..."

Wiki writes about Koh Samui Airport, "Samui International Airport, also known as Ko Samui Airport or Koh Samui Airport, is a privately owned airport on the island of Ko Samui (Koh Samui) in Thailand...The airport has two terminals (Domestic & International). The International terminal is located about 50 metres north of the domestic. Samui Airport is located near the Big Buddha Pier where ferries depart to Ko Pha Ngan. High speed ferries to Koh Tao and Chumphon depart from the Maenam Beach Pier, approximately 6 km north-west of the airport..."

Wiki writes about Lop Buri, " Lopburi is the capital city of Lopburi Province in Thailand. It is located about 150 kilometres north-east of Bangkok. As of 2006 it has a population of 26,500. The town (thesaban mueang) covers the whole tambon Tha Hin and parts of Thale Chup Son of Mueang Lopburi district, a total area of 6.85 km¬≤..."

Wiki writes about the Boeing 737, "The Boeing 737 is a short- to medium-range twinjet narrow-body airliner. Originally developed as a shorter, lower-cost twin-engined airliner derived from Boeing's 707 and 727, the 737 has developed into a family of nine passenger models with a capacity of 85 to 215 passengers. The 737 is Boeing's only narrow-body airliner in production, with the -600, -700, -800, and -900ER variants currently being built. A re-engined and redesigned version, the 737 MAX, is set to debut in 2017..."

title: Phare Circus: Finding a new home
tags: Phare Cambodian Circus|Cambodia (Country)|Performing arts|circus|entertainment|Social Enterprise (Organization Type)|fundraising|Arts|Non-governmental Organization (Non-profit Designation)|Battambang (City/Town/Village)|Siem Reap (City/Town/Village)|Angkor Wat (Place Of Worship)|Angkor Archeological Park|nightlife
description:
Moving from rented space to a permanent home in Siem Reap, Cambodia.

Youth from inconceivably difficult social and economic circumstances discover their beauty and talent at Phare Ponleu Selpak NGO school, allowing them to transform their lives through art. Phare Performing Social Enterprise provides them gainful employment so they can support themselves and their families. 

The performance venue in Siem Reap has been a huge success, reaching the top of TripAdvisor and Lonely Planet recommendations. There are nightly performances where these young Cambodian artists can make a decent living doing something they love. The energy is amazing, but the very existence of the venue is now uncertain. The booming tourism industry is causing rents and real estate prices to rise dramatically, soon to be out of our reach. The lease will be up soon and it's uncertain if the landlord will even renew. 

The only way for Phare to continue this program is to purchase land for a stable, secure, permanent home. If not done soon, the price will be too high for this to even be an option. 

Uniquely Cambodian.....Daringly Modern..... Absolutely Transformative

Expect the unexpected!

https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC0k-GNzAaHM9l2DKTFolj3w?sub_confirmation=1

description:
Dhamma talk with Q&A session offered by Venerable Ajahn Amaro, abbot of Wat Amaravati in England, a monastery in the Thai forest tradition of Ajahn Chah 
https://www.amaravati.org

'Winning and Losing: Life's Ups and Downs and the Buddha's Middle Way'
23rd June, 2014 (18.30 - 20.30)
Meditation Hall
BuddhadƒÅsa Indapa√±√±o Archives, Bangkok

For other teachings by Ven. Ajahn Amaro, please visit:
https://www.amaravati.org/speakers/ajahn-amaro/
https://www.abhayagiri.org/talks/teachers/7-ajahn-amaro
http://www.bia.or.th/en/index.php/teachings-at-the-centre/forest-sangha/ven-ajahn-amaro-audios

About Ven. Ajahn Amaro:
Born in England in 1956, Ven. Amaro Bhikkhu received a BSc. in Psychology and Physiology from the University of London. Spiritual searching led him to Thailand, where he went to Wat Pah Nanachat, a Forest Tradition monastery established for Western disciples of Thai meditation master Ajahn Chah, who ordained him as a bhikkhu in 1979. Soon afterwards he returned to England and joined Ajahn Sumedho at the newly established Chithurst Monastery. He resided for many years at Amaravati Buddhist Monastery, making trips to California every year during the 1990s.

In June 1996 he established Abhayagiri Monastery in Redwood Valley, California, where he was co-Abbot with Ajahn Pasanno until 2010. He then returned to Amaravati to become Abbot of this large monastic community.

Ajahn Amaro has written a number of books, including an account of an 830-mile trek from Chithurst to Harnham Vihara called 'Tudong: The Long Road North,' republished in the expanded book 'Silent Rain.' His other publications include 'Small Boat, Great Mountain' (2003), 'Rain on the Nile' (2009) and 'The Island: An Anthology of the Buddha's Teachings on Nibbana' (2009) co-written with Ajahn Pasanno, a guide to meditation called 'Finding the Missing Peace' and other works dealing with various aspects of Buddhism.

title: Capacity building through Participatory Video in Myanmar
tags: Capacity building|participatory video|communities empowerment|enact change|child's rights to education|poor basic infrastructure|floodings in Myanmar|Myanmar Delta region|community engagement|accountability|InsightShare|Myanmar|Burma|Rights-Based Approach|HRBA|Participation|Church of Sweden|Lutheran World Federation|Facilitation|Participatory Media|Community Video|Community Development|digital skills|local villages|capacity building workshop
description:
What happens when local villagers are trained to enact change on their own? Capacity building tools such as Participatory Video enhance community empowerment for the long term. 

In August 2013, a one-week capacity building workshop in facilitating participatory video took place along the Delta region of Myanmar. The workshop, designed and implemented by InsightShare on behalf of The Church of Sweden in partnership with the Lutheran World Federation Myanmar, aimed to facilitate sessions for representatives from four local villages that were already organised to take local action but lacked digital skills on participatory video. 

At the participatory video training, some of the group members learnt how to use digital equipment for the first time, gaining new digital skills and practical experience in the field to initiate processes by themselves and in between communities. The video shows the participants‚Äô journey, going from the first days of training until the post-training assignments reflections. It also provides insights from the participants while they were putting in practice the methods they learnt to help each community.

In this particular programme, participatory video functioned as a capacity building tool to address key issues each community along the Delta region in Myanmar was facing, such as child's rights to education, poor basic infrastructure and floodings. By participating in the programme, participants of Sar Oh Chaung, Ah Si Ka Lay, Bogaley and Twantay villages were able to identify their strengths and weaknesses to take further action on collective issues.

InsightShare is a community development organisation committed to improving and shaping the use of Participatory Video in all its forms. We are leading practitioners in Participatory Video and we work with organisations wishing to harness Participatory Media as a community engagement, accountability and people-led development tool: https://insightshare.org

Founded in 1976, this River Kwai Jungle Rafts Resort is still really popular nowadays, with thanks to the unique concept. title: Thailand‚Äôs Top 5 Riverside Resorts and Hotels in Kanchanaburi ‚Äì Nature, Luxury, Adventure, Culture
tags: Kanchanaburi|Adventure|Thailand|river kwai|river kwai noi|saiyok|floating hotels|floating resorts|floating villas|hotspring resort|hotspring|nature hotels|riverside hotels|riverfront hotels|jungle resorts|Top kanchanaburi hotels|best kanchanaburi hotels|tented camp|tented camping resort|glamping
description:
RIVER KWAI JUNGLE RAFTS 
Accessible only by a short ride on a longtailed boat through beautiful scenery, The River Kwai Jungle Rafts is a true floating hotel. With its ecolodge concept, it has made top ecotourism listings and won several theme and nature awards. It is a perfect place quiet relaxation. All floating rooms are tucked into a floating bamboo lodge moored along the historical River Kwai surrounded by lush green mountains and jungle. 
The entire hotel does NOT use electricity but rather utilizes traditional lamps at night maintaining a true eco hideaway in nature. This tropical outpost affords plenty of activities, from to riding a friendly elephant through a Mon traditional village and temples , to enjoying traditional Mon folk dances every evening, to water sports like popular  'river jump'. Lifejackets are provided in each guestroom. Guests can simply jump from one end of the floating hotel and float along down the river and climb up at other end. 

THE FLOATHOUSE RIVER KWAI
Elegant in its distinctive boutique style, The FloatHouse River Kwai Resort aims to be the world's best floating resort. The only way to reach the resort is by boat as it actually floats on a fast-flowing river surrounded by thick green jungle.  Each luxurious and spacious floating villa is totally private and rich in custom tailored-made teakwood furniture with thatched roofing. The design is delightfully impressive with exotic decorations including natural materials and ropes. Guests can enjoy amazing panoramic scenery from the swing chair on each private outdoor veranda by the River Kwai. The signature views of the resort are those of the rocky cliff on the opposite side of the river.  
Developed with the eco-conscious in mind, The FloatHouse River Kwai Resort is built from local materials and it is staffed mainly by the local community. 
The FloatHouse River Kwai offers plenty of excursions and sightseeing providing guests with a destination rich in nature, history and culture.

RIVER KWAI RESOTEL 
River Kwai RESOTEL is a serene hideaway surrounded by verdant greenery and mountain ranges beside the Kwai Noi River. The resort offers individual thatched roof cottage accommodation for utmost privacy and comfort. The resort is located just by Saiyok National Park making it easy for the resort guests to walk or bike to Lawa Cave, a stalagmites and stalactites cave in the national park.
Guests can enjoy the turquoise swimming pool and river pier with daybeds for lounging amidst the jungle. The resort offers a variety of traditional and soothing  herbal Thai massages.  In the evening, the resort restaurant presents fine local and international dishes and guests are able to attend local cultural performances on the resort grounds.

HOME PHUTOEY RIVER KWAI RESORT
Home Phutoey River Kwai Resort is a boutique river resort well known as a family holiday adventure park. Travellers can enjoy various activities such as bathing in the natural hotspring pool, exploring the historical railway sights and visiting the museum and enjoying the amazing TREETOP ADVENTURE, a series of ziplines across treetops in a thick green tropical jungle.
The resort guest rooms provide personalized comfort with individual bungalow style houses rich with teakwood d√©cor and modern comfort.  The resort is set in lush green gardens with stunning mountain and river views ideal for taking in the evening. ¬¨¬¨¬¨

HINTOK RIVER CAMP @HELLFIRE PASS 
Hintok River Camp @Hellfire Pass sits on a mountain ridge overlooking the River Kwai in Kanchanaburi. This glamping site is near the world famous historical site, Hellfire Pass. Spread across a grassy lawn, each spacious stylish safari tents is an oasis of the comfort with en-suite bathroom, individually controlled air con and spacious private verandas. 
Guests are welcome to use one of the camp's mountain bikes. Close by is 'Hellfire Pass trekking trails' and 'Hellfire Pass Museum', must-visit World War II sites. It is home to the famous ' railway cutting' built by the Prisoners of War. 
Other popular guest activities include the wading in natural spring pool or enjoying a barbecue campfire dinner under the moonlight and dazzling stars.

title: Capacity building through Participatory Video in Myanmar
tags: Capacity building|participatory video|communities empowerment|enact change|child's rights to education|poor basic infrastructure|floodings in Myanmar|Myanmar Delta region|community engagement|accountability|InsightShare|Myanmar|Burma|Rights-Based Approach|HRBA|Participation|Church of Sweden|Lutheran World Federation|Facilitation|Participatory Media|Community Video|Community Development|digital skills|local villages|capacity building workshop
description:
What happens when local villagers are trained to enact change on their own? Capacity building tools such as Participatory Video enhance community empowerment for the long term. 

In August 2013, a one-week capacity building workshop in facilitating participatory video took place along the Delta region of Myanmar. The workshop, designed and implemented by InsightShare on behalf of The Church of Sweden in partnership with the Lutheran World Federation Myanmar, aimed to facilitate sessions for representatives from four local villages that were already organised to take local action but lacked digital skills on participatory video. 

At the participatory video training, some of the group members learnt how to use digital equipment for the first time, gaining new digital skills and practical experience in the field to initiate processes by themselves and in between communities. The video shows the participants‚Äô journey, going from the first days of training until the post-training assignments reflections. It also provides insights from the participants while they were putting in practice the methods they learnt to help each community.

In this particular programme, participatory video functioned as a capacity building tool to address key issues each community along the Delta region in Myanmar was facing, such as child's rights to education, poor basic infrastructure and floodings. By participating in the programme, participants of Sar Oh Chaung, Ah Si Ka Lay, Bogaley and Twantay villages were able to identify their strengths and weaknesses to take further action on collective issues.

InsightShare is a community development organisation committed to improving and shaping the use of Participatory Video in all its forms. We are leading practitioners in Participatory Video and we work with organisations wishing to harness Participatory Media as a community engagement, accountability and people-led development tool: https://insightshare.org

title: Thailand‚Äôs Top 5 Riverside Resorts and Hotels in Kanchanaburi ‚Äì Nature, Luxury, Adventure, Culture
tags: Kanchanaburi|Adventure|Thailand|river kwai|river kwai noi|saiyok|floating hotels|floating resorts|floating villas|hotspring resort|hotspring|nature hotels|riverside hotels|riverfront hotels|jungle resorts|Top kanchanaburi hotels|best kanchanaburi hotels|tented camp|tented camping resort|glamping
description:
RIVER KWAI JUNGLE RAFTS 
Accessible only by a short ride on a longtailed boat through beautiful scenery, The River Kwai Jungle Rafts is a true floating hotel. With its ecolodge concept, it has made top ecotourism listings and won several theme and nature awards. It is a perfect place quiet relaxation. All floating rooms are tucked into a floating bamboo lodge moored along the historical River Kwai surrounded by lush green mountains and jungle. 
The entire hotel does NOT use electricity but rather utilizes traditional lamps at night maintaining a true eco hideaway in nature. This tropical outpost affords plenty of activities, from to riding a friendly elephant through a Mon traditional village and temples , to enjoying traditional Mon folk dances every evening, to water sports like popular  'river jump'. Lifejackets are provided in each guestroom. Guests can simply jump from one end of the floating hotel and float along down the river and climb up at other end. 

THE FLOATHOUSE RIVER KWAI
Elegant in its distinctive boutique style, The FloatHouse River Kwai Resort aims to be the world's best floating resort. The only way to reach the resort is by boat as it actually floats on a fast-flowing river surrounded by thick green jungle.  Each luxurious and spacious floating villa is totally private and rich in custom tailored-made teakwood furniture with thatched roofing. The design is delightfully impressive with exotic decorations including natural materials and ropes. Guests can enjoy amazing panoramic scenery from the swing chair on each private outdoor veranda by the River Kwai. The signature views of the resort are those of the rocky cliff on the opposite side of the river.  
Developed with the eco-conscious in mind, The FloatHouse River Kwai Resort is built from local materials and it is staffed mainly by the local community. 
The FloatHouse River Kwai offers plenty of excursions and sightseeing providing guests with a destination rich in nature, history and culture.

RIVER KWAI RESOTEL 
River Kwai RESOTEL is a serene hideaway surrounded by verdant greenery and mountain ranges beside the Kwai Noi River. The resort offers individual thatched roof cottage accommodation for utmost privacy and comfort. The resort is located just by Saiyok National Park making it easy for the resort guests to walk or bike to Lawa Cave, a stalagmites and stalactites cave in the national park.
Guests can enjoy the turquoise swimming pool and river pier with daybeds for lounging amidst the jungle. The resort offers a variety of traditional and soothing  herbal Thai massages.  In the evening, the resort restaurant presents fine local and international dishes and guests are able to attend local cultural performances on the resort grounds.

HOME PHUTOEY RIVER KWAI RESORT
Home Phutoey River Kwai Resort is a boutique river resort well known as a family holiday adventure park. Travellers can enjoy various activities such as bathing in the natural hotspring pool, exploring the historical railway sights and visiting the museum and enjoying the amazing TREETOP ADVENTURE, a series of ziplines across treetops in a thick green tropical jungle.
The resort guest rooms provide personalized comfort with individual bungalow style houses rich with teakwood d√©cor and modern comfort.  The resort is set in lush green gardens with stunning mountain and river views ideal for taking in the evening. ¬¨¬¨¬¨

HINTOK RIVER CAMP @HELLFIRE PASS 
Hintok River Camp @Hellfire Pass sits on a mountain ridge overlooking the River Kwai in Kanchanaburi. This glamping site is near the world famous historical site, Hellfire Pass. Spread across a grassy lawn, each spacious stylish safari tents is an oasis of the comfort with en-suite bathroom, individually controlled air con and spacious private verandas. 
Guests are welcome to use one of the camp's mountain bikes. Close by is 'Hellfire Pass trekking trails' and 'Hellfire Pass Museum', must-visit World War II sites. It is home to the famous ' railway cutting' built by the Prisoners of War. 
Other popular guest activities include the wading in natural spring pool or enjoying a barbecue campfire dinner under the moonlight and dazzling stars.

title: Khao San Road in Bangkok - Best Bangkok Street Food - Pad Thai
tags: Thanon Khao San|Backpacker road|Cheap food in Bangkok|Street vendors|Bangkok attractions|Bangkok sights|Street food in Bangkok|Phad Thai|padthai|Bangkok Travel Videos|Bangkok Travel Information|Bangkok Videos|What to do in Bangkok|What to See in Bangkok|How to make Pad Thai|Pad Thai|What to Eat in Bangkok|Best Bangkok Street Food|Khaosan Road|Pad Thai on Khao San Road|Thai Street Food in Bangkok|Thai Fast Food|Thailand|Bangkok|Bangkok Backpackers
description:
We are on Khao San Road or Khaosan Road in Bangkok, Thailand. Khao San Road has been described as THE backpacker central in the whole world. This is the place where all backpackers come and apparently can live on a shoe string budget - many of the backpackers only stay on and around this street when visiting Bangkok... there is loads to see in Bangkok so don¬¥t make that mistake. On a shoestring budget? looking for cheap Thai street food? Just take a walk down the street and choose from freshly pressed juices, ice cream, corn on the cob, grilled chickens, BBQ sausages and stir fried noodles such as Pad Thai..

We chose the Pad Thai and definitely did not regret it. It was freshly made and the portion was more than generous, we were not hungry afterwards. This video footage shows the skillful art of the lady stir frying this fantastic Thai dish for my wife and I. It was delicious and should most definitely be on any travelers "what street food to try list"!! If streetfoods not your thing try it in one of the local restaurants were you are eating. This Thai "National Dish" is not to be missed. I prefer my Pad Thai without the sweetener, and therefore ask them not to put Palm Sugar in the dish. 

Some of the ingredients in Pad Thai include:
- soaked dried rice noodles which are stir-fried with eggs 
- chopped firm tofu. Tofu is made by coagulating soy milk and pressing the resulting curds
- flavored with tamarind pulp and fish sauce
- bean sprouts and a meat such as chicken or prawns

Pad Thai is normally served with lime wedges and finely chopped peanuts. I like to pour fresh Thai chilli/soya sauce over the dish.

In 2011 in a poll conducted by CNN, readers voted Pad Thai number 5 as one of the world's 50 most delicious foods. Be it in a restaurant or at a real Thai street-food seller don¬¥t miss out on tasting Pad Thai when you visit Bangkok or any other part of Thailand, you wont regret it. A plate costs around 50 Baht, that's under 2 US dollars.

title: Patong Beach Street Food - Nutella and banana pancake - Thai streetfood in Phuket, Thailand
tags: Patong Beach Thailand|Thai street food|Thai street pancake|Chocolate|Milk|Street vendor|Pancake stands|Pancake cart|Pancake sales|How to make pancakes|tourism|Patong Beach attractions|Patong Beach Road|How to make a pancake|streetfood|Thai streetfood|Phuket Travel Videos|Phuket Travel Information Videos|Phuket videos|Patong Beach Videos|Patong|Thai Street Food in Phuket|Pancakes with Nutella and Banana|Thai Pancakes|Thailand|Thai Street Food|Phuket Food
description:
We are on the Beach Road in Patong Beach located on the island of Phuket, Thailand. Its night time and we are heading back to our hotel after yet another fantastic Thai dinner. What better way to end the evening off than with a delicious Patong Beach pancake for dessert. We are standing at this street vendor waiting for a Nutella and Banana Pancake. 

Watch the process of how this pancake is lovingly made and then cut and served. This pancake master makes it look so easy. This was not the only time we stopped by at this lady for a dessert pancake on our way home in the Patong evening. Don¬¥t miss out on these crepes there are plenty of choices as you can see and read at the beginning of the video. The price of these delicious pancakes were between 40 and 50 Thai Bahts (under 2 US Dollars) and the combinations included:
- Banana and chocolate pancakes (crepes)
- Banana and caramel pancakes (crepes)
- Banana and honey pancakes (crepes)
- Cinnamon and sugar pancakes (crepes)
- Banana and Lemon and sugar pancakes (crepes)
- Lemon and sugar pancakes (crepes)
- Honey pancakes (crepes)
- Strawberry and chocolate pancakes (crepes)
- Butter and sugar pancakes (crepes)
- Nutella and Peanut Butter pancakes (crepes)
- Banana and condensed milk pancakes (crepes)
- Banana and egg milk pancakes (crepes)
- Coconut and chocolate pancakes (crepes)

Just as there are must see attractions in Phuket or in Patong Beach, there are must try street foods when visiting Patong Beach and most other touristy Thailand places, in this case the Must eat food is a freshly made Patong Beach Pancake.

title: Patong Beach - Local bus from Patong Beach to Phuket Town - Phuket attractions
tags: Thailand|Patong Beach|Bus from Patong to Phuket|Phuket Town|Tuk Tuks|Patong Merlin Hotel|Patong Beach Road|Bangla Boxing Stadium|Vintage bus|Patong public transport|Tourism|Patong|Bus|Phuket Travel Videos|Phuket Travel Information|Phuket Travel Information Videos|Phuket Public Transport|Phuket|Phuket Local Bus|Buses in Phuket|Punlic Transport in Phuket|Phuket Bus Service|Getting around Phuket|How to get around Phuket
description:
We are in Patong Beach which lies on the island of Phuket in Thailand. My wife and I have decided that we would like to visit Phuket Town for the day, and rather than take a taxi there we would like to try the normal public transportation services. Our bus (the Patong Beach Bus Stop) is located right down in the Southern end of Patong Beach actually almost opposite or close to the Patong Merlin Hotel. 

The journey to Phuket Town from Patong Beach cost around 50 Baht and probably took alot longer than a taxi. The ride was however very pleasant and it was a good way to "mingle" with the local Thai people who where also heading for Phuket Town. The bus was eventually full, yet there was always space for one more person. Nice to see the younger generation offering their seats too the older people. Phuket Town is definitely one of the main must see attractions on Phuket Island. Wherever you are living we highly recommend that you try getting there by local bus.

Our footage starts on Patong Beach Road. Watch out for Tuk Tuks, Bangla Boxing Stadium announcements, the Patong beachfront, Jet skis, the Patong Merlin Hotel, McDonalds, Burger King...

Hope you enjoy the video. Please feel free to leave a Comment, Question,  Like and/or Subscribe to our channel for more travel videos like this.

title: Bach Ma (White Horse) Temple-Hanoi's Oldest Temple (With Historical Facts)
tags: Bach Ma Temple|Bach Ma Temple Hanoi|Hanoi Temples|buddhist temples in vietnam|White Horse Temple|Hanoi|buddhist temples|King Ly Thai To
description:
Bach Ma (White Horse) Temple is the oldest temple in Hanoi. It was originally built in 1010 but the current structure dates from the 18th Century. Legend has it that King Ly Thai To built the temple after seeing an apparition of a white horse. You can see a statue of the legendary white horse inside the temple.

title: Patong Beach - Drive into Patong Beach via Patong City Hill - Phuket, Thailand
tags: Patong Shooting range|Patong City|Chinese shrine|Patong City sign|Arriving at Patong Beach|Patong City Hill|Patong drive|Driving to Patong from|Tuk Tuk|Family Mart|Beach Road|Rat-U-Thit|Thai|Phuket Travel videos|Phuket Travel Information|Phuket Travel Information Videos|Phuket Public Transport|Patong Beach Bus|Patong|Patong Beach|Phuket|Patong Hill|What to do in Phuket|What to see in Phuket|Thailand|How to get around in Phuket|Phuket Buses
description:
Watch all our THAILAND TRAVEL VIDEOS, Link in comments section below. We have just arrived on the Thailand holiday island of Phuket. We are sitting in a chartered bus on our way to Patong Beach (Patong City). Our footage starts at the foot of Patong Hill where we quickly pass the Pa tong Shooting Club. After the shooting club look out for the large Patong City Sign on the hill, now you know your destination is near. 

Listen for our bus and other cars and motorcycles beeping their horns at the top of the hill, we are passing a Chinese shrine (Beeping the horn is for good luck, good health or...). Once we have passed the shrine on Patong Hill we begin the slow descent into Patong City and you start to see short glimpses of the sea and the city. From here on you start to get a feeling of the atmosphere of Patong Beach in the morning. Watch out for the Family Mart (the chain of kiosks like 7-Eleven) and the Tuk Tuks not to mention the mobile food carts already selling breakfast snacks to customers. Also watch out for Beach Road and Rat-U-Thit which we drive on towards the end of the video footage.  The time is around 7:30 am. We stayed at the Patong Merlin a fantastic Resort. Enjoy the drive into Patong City.

Hope you enjoy the video. Please feel free to leave a Comment, Like or Subscribe to our Channel for more travel videos like this.

When Ho Chi Minh was President of North Vietnam, he refused to live at the luxurious Presidential Palace because he wanted to empathize with the poor people of his country and didn't want to send the wrong message.
